ace, London\n| type        = Statue\n| location    = Forecourt of 16 [[Carlton House Terrace]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.506590|-0.130659|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = {{circa|1898\u20131902|sortable=yes}}\n| artist      = {{sortname|Thomas|Brock}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 5 February 1902 by [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|Lord Salisbury]] in the [[Junior Constitutional Club]], Piccadilly; sold in 1940. Moved to the present site in 1971, when this building was being used as an annexe of the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=20\u201321}}</ref>\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Victoria Memorial London.JPG\n| subject     = {{sort|Victoria|[[Victoria Memorial, London|Victoria Memorial]]}}<br />{{small|[[Queen Victoria]]}}\n| commonscat  = Victoria Memorial, London\n| type        = Memorial with sculpture\n| location    = Queen Victoria Memorial&nbsp;Gardens, [[The Mall, London|The&nbsp;Mall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.501855|-0.140619|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1901\u20131924\n| artist      = {{sortname|Thomas|Brock}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 16 May 1911 by George V. Brock was adamant that he, and not Aston Webb, was responsible for the architectural design of the memorial. Despite never having travelled to France, he produced a work that was convincingly abreast with ''[[Belle \u00c9poque|belle \u00e9poque]]'' fashion.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=125\u201331}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1273864 Grade I]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Memorial to The Royal Marines.jpg\n| subject     = [[Royal Marines Memorial]]\n| commonscat  = Royal Marines Memorial, The Mall\n| type        = Memorial with sculpture\n| location    = [[The Mall, London|The Mall]]\n| coordinate