rruthers|former Prime Minister of New South Wales]], who wrote to ''[[The Times]]'' complaining of the lack of a statue to Captain Cook in London.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=139\u201340}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1239083 Grade II]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Florence Nightingale statue.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Nightingale|[[Statue of Florence Nightingale, London|Statue]] of [[Florence Nightingale]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Florence Nightingale, London\n| type        = Statue\n| location    = Waterloo Place\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5073|-0.1326|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1915\n| artist      = {{sortname|Arthur George|Walker}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Thomas Henry|Wyatt}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 24 February 1915. The last of a group of three memorials with a Crimean theme on Waterloo Place. The plinth is a copy of that of the statue of [[Sidney Herbert, 1st Baron Herbert of Lea|Lord Herbert]], and is decorated with bronze reliefs of scenes from Nightingale's life.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=401\u201303}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1066143 Grade II]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Scott statue 1.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Scott|Statue of [[Robert&nbsp;Falcon Scott]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of Robert Falcon Scott, London\n| type        = Statue\n| location    = Waterloo Place\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5069|-0.1319|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1915\n| artist      = {{sortname|Kathleen|Scott}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 5 November 1915 by [[Arthur Balfour]]. The sculptor was Captain Scott's widow; she produced a marble replica for [[Christchurch]], New Zealand.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=403\u201305}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1357334 Grade II]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Edward VII equestrian London 1.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Edward 7|Statue of [[Edward&nbsp;VII]]}}\n| commonscat  = King Edward VII Statue, Waterloo Place, London SW1\n| type        = Equestrian statue\n| location    = Waterloo Place\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5067|-0.1321|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1921\n| artist      = {{sortname|Bertram|Mackennal}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Edwin|Lutyens}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 20 July 1921 by George V. Edward VII is depicted in Field Marshal's uniform. Stands on the site previously occupied by the equestrian statue of [[Robert Napier, 1st Baron Napier of Magdala|Lord Napier]] now at [[Queen's Gate]], Kensington.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=405\u201308}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1273712 Grade II]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Army and Navy Club War Memorial.JPG\n| subject     = [[Army and Navy&nbsp;Club]] War&nbsp;Memorial\n| commonscat  =\n| type        = Statue\n| location    = Outside the Army and Navy Club, [[Pall Mall, London|Pall Mall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.506126|-0.135618|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1923\u20131926\n| artist      = {{sortname|Basil|Gotto|nolink=1}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Originally stood in the Victorian clubhouse, which was demolished around 1962. The memorial went into storage at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]. In 2001 it was returned to the club and displayed in a glass case outside its 1960s building.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|p=179}}</ref>\n| designation = {{n/a}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of Mary of Nazareth, Piccadilly.jpg\n| subject     = ''Mary of Nazareth''\n| commonscat  =\n| type        = Statue\n| location    = Churchyard of [[St James's Church, Piccadilly|St James's]], [[Piccadilly]]\n| coor