t2 = Pevsner |first2 = Nikolaus\n | year = 2003\n | title = London 6: Westminster\n | series = The Buildings of England\n | location    = London and New Haven\n | publisher = Yale University Press\n | isbn = 978-0-300-09595-1\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n | ref = harv\n | last = Karlin | first = Daniel\n | year = 2019\n | title = Street Songs: Writers and Urban Songs and Cries, 1800\u20131925\n | series = Clarendon Lectures in English\n | location = Oxford\n | publisher = Oxford University Press\n | isbn = 978-0198792352\n}}\n\n* {{citation\n | ref = harv\n | last = Ward-Jackson | first = Philip\n | year = 2011\n | title = Public Sculpture of Historic Westminster: Volume 1\n | series = Public Sculpture of Britain\n | volume = 14\n | location    = Liverpool\n | publisher = Liverpool University Press\n | isbn = 978-1-84631-691-3\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Public art in London}}\n{{Portal bar|Lists|London|Visual arts}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of public art in the City of Westminster|Saint James's]]\n[[Category:St James's|*Public art]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Crimean War Memorial (42160918222).jpg|thumb|280px|The [[Statue of Florence Nightingale, London|statue of Florence Nightingale]], the [[Crimean War Memorial]] and the [[Statue of Sidney Herbert, London|statue of Sidney Herbert]], Waterloo Place]]\n\nThis is a '''list of public art in [[St James's]]''', a district in the [[City of Westminster]], [[London]].\n\nSt James's lies to the north of [[St James's Park]], a former hunting ground attached to [[St James's Palace]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|pp=580\u201381}}</ref> [[The Mall, London|The Mall]], marking the northern boundary of the park, was transformed into a major thoroughfare in the 1900s by [[Aston Webb]] as part of the national memorial to [[Queen Victoria]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=655}}</ref> Its focal point looking west is the [[Victoria Memorial, London|Victoria Memorial]] designed by [[Thomas Brock]], one of several memorials set along its axis from the early 20th century onwards. To the east The Mall joins [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]]'s processional route (which originally connected [[Carlton House]] to [[Regent's Park]]) at [[Carlton House Terrace]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|pp=436 and 440}}</ref> The part of this route within St James's includes Waterloo Place, described as \"one of the more dramatic pieces of town planning in London\" and lined with statues and memorials mainly of a military character.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|pp=445 and 447\u201348}}</ref> Elsewhere in the district, the Economist Plaza hosted changing displays of contemporary sculpture in the early 21st century; this programme came to an end in 2010 after running for over ten years.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.contemporaryartsociety.org/consultancy/projects/the-economist-plaza-commissions/|title=The Economist Plaza Commissions|publisher=Contemporary Art Society|accessdate=22 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122201148/http://www.contemporaryartsociety.org/consultancy/projects/the-economist-plaza-commissions/|archivedate=22 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Public art header|show_architect=yes|show_material=no|show_dimensions=no|show_owner=no}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of William III, St James Square.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|William 3|[[Equestrian statue of William III, London|Statue]] of [[William III of England|William&nbsp;III]]}}\n| commonscat  = Equestrian statue of William III, St James's Square, London\n| type        = Equestrian statue\n| location    = [[St James's Square]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.507221|-0.135311|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1807\n| artist      = {{Sort|Bacon|[[John Bacon (sculptor, 1777\u20131859)|John Bacon, Jr.]]}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Very likely to a design of the sculptor's father [[John Bacon (sculptor, born 1740)|John Bacon, Senior]], dating to 1794. The design is probably inspired by [[John Michael Rysbrack]]'s [[Equestrian statue of William III, Bristol|equestrian statue of William III]] in Queen Square, Bristol.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1235855 |desc=Statue of William III (in centre of Square) |accessdate=21 November 2013 |fewer-links=x}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1235855 Grade I]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Athenaeum Club statue (25300078589).jpg\n| commonscat  = Statue of Athena (Baily), Athenaeum Club\n| subject     = ''[[Pallas Athene]]''\n| location    = [[Athenaeum Club, London|Athenaeum Club]], Waterloo Place\n| date        = {{circa|1828|sortable=yes}}\n| artist      = {{sortname|Edward Hodges|Baily}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Decimus|Burton}}\n| type        = Statue\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1225842 Grade I]}}\n| notes       =\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Duke of York statue from The Mall.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|York|[[Duke of York Column]]}}<br />{{small|[[Prince Frederick, Duke of York and&nbsp;Albany]]}}\n| commonscat  = Duke of York Column\n| type        = Statue on column\n| location    = Waterloo Place\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.506331|-0.131761|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1829\u20131834\n| artist      = {{sortname|Richard|Westmacott}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Benjamin Dean|Wyatt}}\n| notes       = The Duke, in his [[Order of the Garter|Garter]] robes, stands atop an [[fluting (architecture)|unfluted]] [[Doric order|Doric column]]. Westmacott intended for the statue to face north towards Regent Street, but William IV, on the Duke of Wellington's advice, requested that it face the [[Horse Guards (building)|Horse Guards]] to the south. The column was completed in 1832 and the statue raised on 3 April 1834.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=385\u201388}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1239383 Grade I]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Statue of George III, Pall Mall SW1.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|George 3|Statue of [[George III of the United Kingdom|George&nbsp;III]]}}\n| commonscat  = Statue of George III, Pall Mall, London\n| type        = Equestrian statue\n| location    = [[Cockspur Street]], facing down [[Pall Mall, London|Pall&nbsp;Mall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5078|-0.1305|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = {{circa|1836|sortable=yes}}\n| artist      = {{sortname|Matthew Cotes|Wyatt}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 3 August 1836 by the [[George V of Hanover|Duke of Cumberland]]. After the King's death in 1820 Wyatt designed an ambitious multi-figure monument, but there were too few subscriptions for the project to go ahead. Fund-raising recommenced in 1831. The statue came to be nicknamed \"the Pigtail and Pump-head\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=32\u201335}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1219890 Grade II]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Buckingham Palace Gates. London. 1905.jpg\n| subject     = [[Buckingham Palace]] Gates\n| commonscat  = Front gates of Buckingham Palace\n| type        = Gates and piers with sculptural decoration\n| location    = Forecourt of Buckingham Palace\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5015|-0.1413|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1850\u20131851 (north); 1904\u20131908 (south); 1911 (centre)\n| artist      = {{sort|Thomas et al.|{{nowrap|[[John Thomas (sculptor)|John Thomas]]}}, {{nowrap|[[William Silver Frith|W. S. Frith]]}}, {{nowrap|[[Walter Gilbert (sculptor)|Walter Gilbert]]}} and {{nowrap|Louis Weingartner}}}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Decimus|Burton}} and [[Aston Webb]]\n| notes       = Burton's gates were installed after the removal of [[Marble Arch]], formerly the ceremonial entrance to the palace. Webb commissioned the [[Bromsgrove Guild of Applied Arts|Bromsgrove Guild]] to produce replicas with minor variations, which were erected on the southern side. The central gates were added at the request of George V.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=133\u201334}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1239251 Grade I]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Crimea monument London 2.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Guards Crimean War Memorial|[[Crimean War Memorial|The Guards Crimean&nbsp;War Memorial]]}}\n| commonscat  = Crimean War Memorial, London\n| type        = Memorial with sculpture\n| location    = Waterloo Place\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5074|-0.1327|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1858\u20131862\n| artist      = {{sortname|John|Bell|dab=sculptor}}\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = The figures at the base of the plinth are of a [[Grenadier Guards|Grenadier]], a [[Fusilier]] and a [[Coldstream Guards|Coldstream Guard]]; the crowning figure represents Honour. They are cast in bronze from cannon captured at the [[Siege of Sevastopol (1854\u20131855)|Siege of Sevastopol]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=388\u201390}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1066141 Grade II]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = The Boy, St James\u2019s Park.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Boy|''The Boy''}}\n| commonscat  = The Greek Boy Fountain, 1863, by Lady von Gleichen\n| type        = Drinking fountain with sculpture\n| location    = St James's Park\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5012|-0.1341|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1863\n| artist      = {{sortname|Charles Henry|Mabey|nolink=1}} <small>for Robert Jackson & Son</small>\n| architect   = {{n/a}}\n| notes       = A marble figure of a boy naked to the waist, set on a granite plinth with marble panels. The badly worn and much vandalised scu