32\"/>\n| designation = {{sort|A|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1239086 Grade I]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Justice by H. C. Binney, 162\u2013165 Piccadilly, London.jpg\n| subject     = ''Justice''\n| location    = 162\u2013165 Piccadilly\n| date        = 1907\u20131909\n| artist      = {{sortname|Hibbert Charles|Binney|nolink=1}}\n| architect   = Runtz & Ford\n| type        = Architectural sculpture\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1226543 Grade II]}}\n| notes       = {{sfn|Bradley|Pevsner|2003|p=559}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Royal Artillery Boer War Memorial.jpg\n| subject     = {{sort|Royal Artillery|[[Royal Artillery Boer War Memorial]]}}\n| commonscat  = Royal Artillery Boer War Memorial\n| type        = Memorial with sculpture\n| location    = [[The Mall, London|The Mall]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.5054|-0.1310|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB-WSM}}\n| date        = 1910\n| artist      = {{sortname|William Robert|Colton}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Aston|Webb}}\n| notes       = Unveiled 20 July 1910 by the [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn|Duke of Connaught]]. Colton was given the commission after Thomas Brock turned it down due to the pressure of other commitments. Few were pleased with the resulting memorial.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ward-Jackson|2011|pp=136\u201338}}</ref>\n| designation = {{sort|C|[https://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1273903 Grade II]}}\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image       = Splendor Sine Occasu.jpg\n| subject     = ''Justice, Progress and Industry'' and the arms of [[British&nbsp;Columbia]]\n| location    = 11 Charles II Street (formerly [[British Columbia House]]), Regent Street St James's fa\u00e7ade\n| date        = {{circa|1914|sortable=yes}}\n| artist      = {{sortname|F. W.|Pomeroy}}\n| architect   = {{sortname|Alfred|Burr|nolink=1}}\n| type        = Architectural sculpture\n| des