0111009072252/http://www.nbr.org/publications/issue.aspx?id=235 Strategic Asia 2011-12: Asia Responds to Its Rising Powers - China and India], edited by Ashley J. Tellis, Travis Tanner, and Jessica Keough ([[National Bureau of Asian Research]], 2011)\n\n* [https://www.academia.edu/7767087/Maritime_Interactions_between_China_and_India Maritime Interactions between China and India: Coastal India and the Ascendancy of Chinese Maritime Power in the Indian Ocean] \n* [https://www.academia.edu/7767082/Maritime_Southeast_Asia_Between_South_Asia_and_China_to_the_Sixteenth_Century Maritime Southeast Asia Between South Asia and China to the Sixteenth Century]\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of China}}\n{{Foreign relations of India}}\n{{BRICS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sino-Indian Relations}}\n[[Category:China\u2013India relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of China|India]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of India|China]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of the Republic of China]]\n[[Category:China\u2013India border]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the People's Republic of China and the Republic of India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}} \n{{Infobox Bilateral relations|China\u2013India|India|China|filetype=svg\n|envoytitle1 =[[List of diplomatic missions of India|Indian Ambassador]]\n|envoy1 = Vikram Misri<ref>{{cite news |title=New Indian envoy Vikram Misri takes charge in Beijing |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/vikram-misri-takes-charge-as-indias-new-envoy-to-china/article25939008.ece |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=2019-01-08 |language=en}}</ref>\n|envoytitle2 = [[List of diplomatic missions of China|Chinese Ambassador]]\n|envoy2 = Sun Weidong<ref>{{cite news |title=New Beijing envoy Weidong takes charge in New Delhi |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/sun-weidong-appointed-china-s-next-ambassador-to-india-119061200542_1.html |work=Business Standard |date=2019-06-28 |language=en}}</ref>\n|mission1=[[Embassy of India, Beijing|Indian Embassy, Beijing]]\n|mission2=[[List of diplomatic missions of China#Asia|Chinese Embassy, New Delhi]]\n}}\n[[File:PM Modi and President Xi.jpg|thumb|244px|President [[Xi Jinping]] of China and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] of India, during the former's state visit to India, September 2014.]]\n[[File:PM Modi and Chinese Premier Li Keqiang at Nay Pyi Taw, Myanmar.jpg|thumb|244px|Premier [[Li Keqiang]] of China and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] of India, during the [[ASEAN Summit]] to [[Myanmar]], September 2014.]]\n'''China\u2013India relations''', also called '''Sino-Indo relations''' or '''Indian-Chinese relations''', refers to the bilateral relationship between the [[China|People's Republic of China]] (PRC) and the [[India|Republic of India]]. Although the relationship has been cordial, there have been border disputes. The modern relationship began in 1950 when India was among the first countries to end formal ties with the Republic of China ([[Taiwan]]) and recognize the PRC as the legitimate government of [[Mainland China]]. China and India are the two [[List of countries by population|most populous countries]] and [[List of countries by real GDP growth rate|fastest growing]] major economies in the world. Growth in diplomatic and economic influence has increased the significance of their bilateral relationship.\n\nCultural and economic relations between China and India date back to ancient times. The [[Silk Road]] not only served as a major [[trade route]] between India and China, but is also credited for facilitating the spread of [[Buddhism]] from India to East Asia.<ref name=Maria>{{cite book\n  |last = Backus\n  |first = Maria\n  |title = Ancient China\n  |publisher = Lorenz Educational Press, 2002\n  |isbn =978-0-7877-0557-2|date = September 2002\n }}</ref> During the 19th century, China's growing opium trade with the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] [[East India Company]] triggered the [[First Opium War|First]] and [[Second Opium War]]s.<ref>{{cite book\n  |last = Janin\n  |first = Hunt\n  |title = The India-China opium trade in the nineteenth century\n  |publisher = McFarland, 1999\n  |isbn =978-0-7864-0715-6|date = January 1999\n }}</ref><ref name=\"Sen2003\">{{cite book|author=Tansen Sen|title=Buddhism, Diplomacy, and Trade: The Realignment of Sino-Indian Relations, 600-1400|url=https://books.google.com/?id=blBTHAY_A4wC&printsec=frontcover&dq=774+787+srivijaya#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=January 2003|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-2593-5}}</ref> During [[World War II]], British-occupied India and China both played a crucial role in halting the progress of [[Imperial Japan]].<ref name=Barbara>{{cite book\n  |last = Williams\n  |first = Barbara\n  |title = World War Two\n  |publisher = Twenty-First Century Books, 2004\n  |isbn = 978-0-8225-0138-1\n  |url-access = registration\n  |url = https://archive.org/details/worldwariipacifi0000will\n  |year = 2005\n }}</ref>\n\nRelations between contemporary China and India have been characterised by [[Origins of the Sino-Indian border dispute|border disputes]], resulting in three [[military conflict]]s &mdash; the [[Sino-Indian War]] of 1962, the [[Chola incident]] in 1967, and the [[1987 Sino-Indian skirmish]].<ref name=\"APCSS\">[http://www.apcss.org/core/BIOS/malik/India-China_Relations.pdf]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In early 2017, the two countries clashed at the [[Doklam plateau]] along the disputed [[Bhutan\u2013China border|Sino-Bhutanese border]].<ref>{{citation |last=Joshi |first=Manoj |authorlink=Manoj Joshi |url=http://www.orfonline.org/research/doklam-start-very-beginning/ |title=Doklam: To start at the very beginning |publisher=Observer Research Foundation |date=2017 |ref={{sfnref|Joshi, Doklam: To start at the very beginning|2017}}}}</ref> However, since the late 1980s, both countries have successfully rebuilt diplomatic and economic ties. In 2008, China became India's largest trading partner and the two countries have also extended their strategic and military relations.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A43053-2005Apr11.html | work=The Washington Post | first=John | last=Lancaster | title=India, China Hoping to 'Reshape the World Order' Together | date=12 April 2005 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209160559/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A43053-2005Apr11.html | archivedate=9 February 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theworldreporter.com/2010/07/why-indo-china-ties-will-be-more.html |title=Why Indo-China ties will be more favourable than Sino-Pak |publisher=Theworldreporter.com |date=7 July 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019172133/http://www.theworldreporter.com/2010/07/why-indo-china-ties-will-be-more.html |archivedate=19 October 2010  }}</ref><ref name=Hindu1>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/indiachina-trade-surpasses-target/article1129785.ece India-China trade surpasses target], ''The Hindu'', 27 January 2011.</ref> Apart from trade and commerce, there are some other areas of mutual interest on which China and India have been cooperating of late. In the words of [[Rejaul Karim Laskar]], a scholar of Indian foreign policy, \"Currently, the two countries are cooperating on a range of international like trade, climate change and reform of the global financial order, among others, to promote common interest\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Laskar|first1=Rejaul|title=Promoting National Interest Through Diplomacy|journal=Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary Diplomatist|date=December 2013|volume=1|issue=9|page=60}}</ref>\n\nDespite growing economic and strategic ties, there are several hurdles for India and the PRC to overcome. India faces trade imbalance heavily in favour of China. The two countries failed to resolve their border dispute and Indian media outlets have repeatedly reported Chinese military incursions into Indian territory.<ref name=WSJ>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124578881101543463|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710060101/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124578881101543463|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 July 2015|title=The China-India Border Brawl|author=Jeff M. Smith today's Wall Street Journal Asia|date=24 June 2009|work=WSJ|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref> Both countries have steadily established military infrastructure along border areas.<ref name=WSJ/><ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_ak-antony-admits-china-incursion_1592435 AK Antony admits China incursion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930132104/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_ak-antony-admits-china-incursion_1592435 |date=30 September 2011 }}, DNA, 28 September 2011.</ref> Additionally, India remains wary about China's strong [[China\u2013Pakistan relations|strategic bilateral relations with Pakistan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/9d5497f0-db8d-11de-9424-00144feabdc0.html|title=China-Pakistan military links upset India|work=Financial Times|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref> while China has expressed concerns about Indian military and economic activities in the disputed [[South China Sea]].<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article2455647.ece China warns India on South China Sea exploration projects] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924173917/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article2455647.ece |date=24 September 2011 }}, ''The Hindu'', 15 September 2011.</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, China stated its position that \"Sino-Indian ties\" could be the most \"important bilateral partnership of the century\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-07/india/32100282_1_asia-pacific-defence-cooperation-defence-secretary | work=The Times Of India | title=US, China woo India for control over Asia-Pacific | date=7 June 2012}}</ref> That month [[Wen Jiabao]], the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier of China]] and [[Manmohan Singh]], the [[Prime Minister of India]] set a goal to increase bilateral trade between the two countries to US$100 billion by 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/India-China-bilateral-trade-set-to-hit-100-billion-by-2015/articleshow/14323128.cms |title=India-China bilateral trade set to hit $100 billion by 2015 - The Times of India |publisher=The Times of India |date=21 June 2012 |accessdate=3 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624220336/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/India-China-bilateral-trade-set-to-hit-100-billion-by-2015/articleshow/14323128.cms |archivedate=24 June 2012  }}</ref>\n\nBilateral trade between China and India touched US$89.6 billion in 2017-18,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/with-us-trade-under-a-cloud-china-opens-to-indian-pharma/articleshow/64958667.cms|title=With US trade under a cloud, China opens to Indian pharma}}</ref> with the trade deficit widening to US$62.9 billion in China's favour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/macro-economy/63-b-trade-deficit-untenable-india-tells-china/article24401094.ece|title=India tells China: $63-b trade deficit untenable|first=Amiti|last=Sen|website=@businessline}}</ref> In 2017, the volume of bilateral trade between India & China stands at US$84.5 billion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/india-china-bilateral-trade-hits-historic-high-of-usd-84-44-bln-in-2017/articleshow/63203371.cms|title=India-China bilateral trade hits historic high of USD 84.44 bln in 2017|date=7 March 2018|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref> This figure excludes bilateral trade between India & Hong Kong which stands at another US$34 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/IiMAWzG8C7MRi85S9OSoUO/Hong-Kong-can-be-Indias-gateway-to-China-Gautam-Bambawale.html|title=Hong Kong can be India's gateway to China: Gautam Bambawale|first=Preeti|last=Dawra|date=23 March 2018|website=www.livemint.com}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2014 [[BBC]] World Service Poll, 23% of Indians view China positively, with 47% expressing a negative view, whereas 27% of Chinese people view India positively, with 35% expressing a negative view.<ref>[http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/country-rating-poll.pdf 2014 World Service Poll] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410000527/http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/country-rating-poll.pdf |date=10 April 2016 }} ''[[BBC]]''</ref> A 2014 survey conducted by the [[Pew Research Center]] showed 72% of Indians were concerned that territorial disputes between China and neighbouring countries could lead to a military conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2014/07/14/chapter-4-how-asians-view-each-other/|title=Chapter 4: How Asians View Each Other|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|accessdate=10 October 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015203043/http://www.pewglobal.org/2014/07/14/chapter-4-how-asians-view-each-other/|archivedate=15 October 2015|date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[President of the People's Republic of China|President of China]], [[Xi Jinping]], was one of the top world leaders to visit [[New Delhi]] after [[Narendra Modi]] took over as [[Prime Minister of India]] in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://www.orfonline.org/research/make-china-indias-natural-ally-for-development/| title= Make China India's natural ally for development| first=Ranjit | last=Goswami | date = 13 May 2015 | accessdate = 14 February 2017|work=Observer Research Foundation}}</ref> India's insistence to raise [[South China Sea]] in various multilateral forums subsequently did not help that beginning once again, the relationship facing suspicion from Indian administration and media alike.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/ranjit-goswami/can-pm-modi-make-china-in_b_7206320.html | title=Can Modi Make China India's Natural Ally for Development? | first=Ranjit | last=Goswami | date=11 May 2015 | accessdate=14 February 2017 | work=The Huffington Post | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214181157/http://www.huffingtonpost.in/ranjit-goswami/can-pm-modi-make-china-in_b_7206320.html | archivedate=14 February 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2020, the 70th anniversary of India-China diplomatic ties, 70 events will be held in celebration by the two countries. Various other activities are also planned.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/india-china-finalise-70-activities-to-celebrate-70-years-of-diplomatic-ties/articleshow/72185751.cms|title=India, China finalise 70 activities to celebrate 70 years of diplomatic ties|date=22 November 2019|website=The Times of India|others=PTI|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==Geographical overview==\n[[File:Sino-Indian Geography.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of Eastern and Southern Asia. <br><hr>(The border between the People's Republic of China and the Republic of India over [[Arunachal Pradesh]]/[[South Tibet]] reflects actual control, without dotted line showing claims.)]]\n\nChina and India are separated by the [[Himalayas]]. China and India today share a border with [[Nepal]] and [[Bhutan]] acting as [[buffer state]]s. Parts of the disputed [[Kashmir]] region claimed by India are claimed and administered by either [[Pakistan]] ([[Azad Kashmir]] and [[Gilgit and Baltistan]]) or by the PRC ([[Aksai Chin]]). The Government of Pakistan on its maps shows the Aksai Chin area as mostly within China and labels the boundary \"Frontier Undefined\" while India holds that Aksai Chin is illegally occupied by the PRC.\n\nChina and India also dispute most of [[Arunachal Pradesh]].  However, both countries have agreed to respect the [[Line of Actual Control]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\n==Early history==\n\n===Antiquity===\n[[File:Madhya pradesh, epoca candella, tirthankara rishabhanatha, x-xi sec.JPG|thumb|left|[[Rishabhanatha]], the founder of [[Jainism]] attained [[nirvana]] near [[Mount Kailash]] in Tibet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1DtuAAAAMAAJ&q=Rishabhanatha+tibet&dq=Rishabhanatha+tibet|title=101 pilgrimages|date=21 August 2006|publisher=Outlook India Pub.|via=Google Books}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Echecs chinois.JPG|thumb|right|[[Xiangqi]], or Chinese chess, which, like [[Chess|Western Chess]] is believed to be descended from the Indian chess game of [[chaturanga]].<ref>Henry Davidson, ''A Short History of Chess'', p. 6.</ref>  The earliest indications reveal the game may have been played as early as the third century BCE.]]\nThe first records of contact between China and India were written during the 2nd century BCE. [[Buddhism]]  was transmitted from India to China in the 1st century CE.<ref>Indian Embassy, Beijing. [http://www.indianembassy.org.cn/DynamicContent.aspx?MenuId=1&SubMenuId=0 ''India-China Bilateral Relations - Historical Ties''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821001742/http://www.indianembassy.org.cn/DynamicContent.aspx?MenuId=1&SubMenuId=0 |date=21 August 2013 }}</ref> Trade relations via the [[Silk Road]] acted as economic contact between the two regions.\n\nChina and India have also had some contact before the transmission of Buddhism. References to a people called the ''[[Chinas]]'', are found in ancient [[Indian literature]]. The [[Indian epic poetry|Indian epic]] ''[[Mahabharata]]'' (c. 5th century BCE) contains references to \"[[China in the Mah\u0101bh\u0101rata|China]]\", which may have been referring to the [[Qin (state)|Qin]] state which later became the [[Qin Dynasty]]. [[Chanakya]] (c. 350-283 BCE), the [[prime minister]] of the [[Maurya Empire]] refers to Chinese [[silk]] as \"cinamsuka\" (Chinese silk dress) and \"cinapatta\" (Chinese silk bundle) in his ''[[Arthashastra]]''.\n\nIn the ''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'', [[Zhang Qian]] (d. 113 BCE) and [[Sima Qian]] (145-90 BCE) make references to \"Shendu\", which may have been referring to the [[Indus River|Indus Valley]] (the [[Sindh]] province in modern Pakistan), originally known as \"Sindhu\" in [[Sanskrit]]. When [[Yunnan]] was annexed by the [[Han Dynasty]] in the 1st century, Chinese authorities reported an Indian \"Shendu\" community living there.<ref>Tan Chung (1998). [http://ignca.nic.in/ks_41019.htm ''A Sino-Indian Perspective for India-China Understanding''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070606221357/http://ignca.nic.in/ks_41019.htm |date=6 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Middle Ages===\n[[File:Shaolinsi.JPG|thumb|The [[Shaolin Monastery]] in [[Dengfeng]], Henan, China.]]\n[[File:Xuanzang Memorial Hall Nalanda.jpg|thumb|Xuanzang Memorial Hall in Nalanda, Bihar, India.]]\nFrom the 1st century onwards, many Indian scholars and monks travelled to China, such as [[Batuo]] ([[floruit|fl.]] 464-495 CE)&mdash;first abbot of the [[Shaolin Monastery]]&mdash;and [[Bodhidharma]]&mdash;founder of [[Zen|Chan/Zen]] Buddhism&mdash;while many Chinese scholars and monks also travelled to India, such as [[Xuanzang]] (b. 604) and [[I Ching (monk)|I Ching]] (635-713), both of whom were students at [[Nalanda|Nalanda University]] in [[Bihar]]. Xuanzang wrote the ''[[Great Tang Records on the Western Regions]]'', an account of his journey to India, which later inspired [[Wu Cheng'en]]'s [[Ming Dynasty]] novel ''[[Journey to the West]]'', one of the [[Four Great Classical Novels]] of [[Chinese literature]].  According to some, St. Thomas the Apostle travelled from India to China and back (see Perumalil, A.C. ''The Apostle in India''. Patna, 1971: 5-54.)\n\n====Tamil dynasties====\n\n{{Main|Relationship of the Cholas with the Chinese}}\n[[File:Rajendra map new.svg|thumb|right|250px|[[Chola Empire]] under [[Rajendra Chola]] c. 1030 C.E.]]\nThe [[Cholas]] maintained good relationship with the [[China|Chinese]]. Arrays of ancient Chinese coins have been found in the Cholas homeland (i.e. [[Thanjavur]], [[Tiruvarur]] and [[Pudukkottai]] districts of Tamil Nadu, India).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article526352.ece|title=Old coins narrate Sino-Tamil story|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605052206/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article526352.ece|archivedate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnder [[Rajaraja Chola]] and his son [[Rajendra Chola]], the Cholas had strong trading links with Chinese [[Song Dynasty]].<ref name=\"his_of_india\">{{Citation|last = Smith|first= Vincent Arthur|title=  The Early History of India|year=1904|publisher= The Clarendon press|pages = 336\u2013358|isbn = 81-7156-618-9}}</ref><!--page #345--><ref name=\"rajendra1\">{{Citation|last = Srivastava|first= Balram|title=  Rajendra Chola|year=1973|publisher=  National Book Trust, India|page = 80|quote = The mission which Rajendra sent to China was essentially a trade mission,...}}</ref><ref name=\"cct\">{{Citation|last = D. Curtin|first= Philip|title=   Cross-Cultural Trade in World History|year=1984|publisher= Cambridge University Press|page = 101|isbn = 0-521-26931-8}}</ref> The [[Chola navy]] conquered the [[Sri Vijaya]] Empire of [[Indonesia]] and [[Malaysia]] and secured a sea trading route to China.<ref name=\"his_of_india\" /><!--page 345-346-->\n\nMany sources describe [[Bodhidharma]], the founder of the [[Zen]] school of [[Buddhism]] in China, as a prince of the [[Pallava dynasty]].<ref>Kamil V. Zvelebil (1987). \"The Sound of the One Hand\", ''Journal of the American Oriental Society'', Vol. 107, No. 1, pp. 125\u2013126.</ref>\n\n====Tang and Harsha dynasties====\n{{see also|China\u2013Nepal_relations#Nepal.2C_Tibet_and_China}}\nDuring the 7th century, [[Tang dynasty]] China gained control over large portions of the [[Silk Road]] and Central Asia. [[Wang Xuance]] had sent a diplomatic mission to northern India, which was embroiled by civil war just following the death of [[Harsha|Emperor Harsha]] (590\u2013647). After the murder of 30 members of this mission by the usurper claimants, Wang fled, and returned with allied [[Nepal]]i and [[Tibet]]an troops to back the opposition. With his forces, Wang captured the capital, while his deputy Jiang Shiren (\u848b\u5e08\u4ec1) captured the usurper and sent him back to [[Emperor Taizong of Tang|Emperor Taizong]] (599-649) in [[Chang'an]] as a prisoner.\n\nDuring the 8th century, the astronomical [[Aryabhata's sine table|table]] of [[Trigonometric functions|sines]] by the [[Indian astronomy|Indian astronomer]] and [[Indian mathematics|mathematician]], [[Aryabhatta]] (476-550), were translated into the [[Chinese astronomy|Chinese astronomical]] and [[Chinese mathematics|mathematical]] book of the ''[[Treatise on Astrology of the Kaiyuan Era]]'' (''Kaiyuan Zhanjing''), compiled in 718 CE during the Tang Dynasty.<ref name=\"needham volume 3 109\">[[Joseph Needham]], Volume 3, p. 109</ref> The ''Kaiyuan Zhanjing'' was compiled by [[Gautama Siddha]], an astronomer and astrologer born in Chang'an, and whose family was originally from India. He was also notable for his translation of the [[Navagraha]] calendar into [[Chinese language|Chinese]].\n\n====Yuan dynasty====\nA rich merchant from the [[Ma'bar Sultanate]], Abu Ali (P'aehali) \u5b5b\u54c8\u91cc (or \u5e03\u54c8\u723e Buhaer), was associated closely with the Ma'bar royal family. After a fallout with the Ma'bar family, he moved to [[Yuan dynasty]] China and received a Korean woman as his wife and a job from the Emperor, the woman was formerly [[w:zh:\u6851\u54e5|\u6851\u54e5]] Sangha's wife and her father was \u8521\u4ec1\u63c6 [[w:ko:\ucc44\uc1a1\ub144|\ucc44\uc1a1\ub144]] Ch'ae In'gyu during the reign of \u5fe0\u70c8 [[Chungnyeol of Goryeo]], recorded in the [[Dongguk Tonggam]], [[Goryeosa]] and [[w:zh:\u7559\u5922\u708e|\u7559\u5922\u708e]] Liu Mengyan's \u4e2d\u4ffa\u96c6 Zhong'anji.<ref name=\"Schottenhammer2008\">{{cite book|author=Angela Schottenhammer|title=The East Asian Mediterranean: Maritime Crossroads of Culture, Commerce and Human Migration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GSA_AaRdgioC&pg=PA138#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2008|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=978-3-447-05809-4|pages=138\u2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821080515/https://books.google.com/books?id=GSA_AaRdgioC&pg=PA138#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=21 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=SEN |first1=TANSEN |title=The Yuan Khanate and India: Cross-Cultural Diplomacy in the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Centuries |journal=Asia Major |date=2006 |volume=19 |issue=1/2 |pages=299\u2013326 |jstor=41649921}}</ref> [[w:zh:\u6851\u54e5|\u6851\u54e5]] Sangha was a Tibetan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sino-platonic.org/complete/spp110_wuzong_emperor.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220223438/http://www.sino-platonic.org/complete/spp110_wuzong_emperor.pdf |archivedate=20 December 2016  }} p. 15.</ref> Tamil Hindu Indian merchants traded in [[Quanzhou]] during the Yuan dynasty.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/behind-chinas-hindu-temples-a-forgotten-history/article4932458.ece|title=Behind China's Hindu temples, a forgotten history|author=Ananth Krishnan|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140621040237/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/behind-chinas-hindu-temples-a-forgotten-history/article4932458.ece|archivedate=21 June 2014|date=19 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gcb643uVtSc|title=China's Hindu temples: A forgotten history|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=16 May 2016|via=YouTube|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310054322/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gcb643uVtSc|archivedate=10 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gcb643uVtSc#t=0|title=China's Hindu temples: A forgotten history|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=16 May 2016|via=YouTube|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310054322/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gcb643uVtSc#t=0|archivedate=10 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/multimedia/dynamic/01523/TH20_PAGE_1_ANANTH_1523758g.jpg|title=Multimedia|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119135250/http://www.thehindu.com/multimedia/dynamic/01523/TH20_PAGE_1_ANANTH_1523758g.jpg|archivedate=19 January 2016}}</ref> Hindu statues were found in Quanzhou dating to this period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel.cnn.com/quanzhou-chinas-forgotten-historic-port-258149/|title=What to do in Quanzhou: China's forgotten historic port - CNN Travel|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305020143/http://travel.cnn.com/quanzhou-chinas-forgotten-historic-port-258149/|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Ming dynasty===\n[[File:Treasure Boat Shipyard - stele pavilion - Calicut stele - P1080100.JPG|thumb|[[Stele]] installed in [[Kozhikode|Calicut]] by [[Zheng He]] (modern replica)]]\n[[File:Chinese nets.jpg|thumb|[[Chinese fishing nets]] in [[Kochi]], Kerala, India.]]\nBetween 1405 and 1433, [[Ming dynasty]] China sponsored a [[Ming treasure voyages|series of seven naval expeditions]] led by Admiral [[Zheng He]]. Zheng He visited numerous Indian kingdoms and ports, including India, [[Bengal]], and [[Ceylon]], [[Persian Gulf]], [[Arabia]], and later expeditions ventured down as far as [[Malindi]] in what is now [[Kenya]]. Throughout his travels, Zheng He liberally dispensed Chinese gifts of silk, [[porcelain]], and other goods. In return, he received rich and unusual presents, including African [[zebras]] and [[giraffes]]. Zheng He and his company paid respect to local [[deities]] and customs, and in Ceylon they erected a monument ([[Galle Trilingual Inscription]]) honouring [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]], [[Allah]], and [[Vishnu]]. Bengal sent twelve diplomatic missions to [[Nanjing]] between 1405 and 1439.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://scroll.in/article/837096/as-mamata-banerjee-seeks-chinese-investment-for-bengal-why-is-delhi-bent-on-playing-spoilsport |title=OBOR: As Mamata seeks Chinese investment for Bengal, why is Delhi bent on playing spoilsport? |date=14 May 2017 |first=Garga |last=Chatterjee |publisher=Scroll Media Inc}}</ref>\n\n===Sino-Sikh War===\n{{Main|Sino-Sikh war}}\nIn the 18th to 19th centuries, the [[Sikh Empire]] expanded into neighbouring lands. It had annexed [[Ladakh]] into the state of [[Jammu]] in 1834. In 1841, they invaded [[Tibet under Qing rule|Tibet]] and overran parts of western Tibet. Chinese forces defeated the Sikh army in December 1841, forcing the Sikh army to withdraw, and in turn entered Ladakh and besieged [[Leh]], where they were in turn defeated by the Sikh Army. At this point, neither side wished to continue the conflict. The Sikhs claimed victory. as the Sikhs were embroiled in tensions with the British that would lead up to the [[First Anglo-Sikh War]], while the Chinese were in the midst of the [[First Opium War]]. The two parties signed a treaty in September 1842, which stipulated no transgressions or interference in the other country's frontiers.<ref name=\"Rubin\">The Sino-Indian Border Disputes, by Alfred P. Rubin, The International and Comparative Law Quarterly, Vol. 9, No. 1. (January 1960), pp. 96-125.</ref>\n\n===British India===\nThe [[British East India Company]] used opium grown in India as export to China. The British used their Indian [[sepoy]]s and the [[British Indian Army]] in the [[Opium Wars]] and [[Boxer Rebellion]] against China. They also used Indian soldiers to guard the Foreign concessions in areas like Shanghai. The Chinese slur \"Yindu A San\" (Indian number three) was used to describe Indian soldiers in British service.\n\n==After independence==\nOn 1 October 1949 the People's Liberation Army defeated the Kuomintang (Nationalist Party). On 15 August 1947, India became federal, democratic republic after its constitution came into effect on 26 January 1950.\n\n[[Jawaharlal Nehru]] based his vision of \"resurgent Asia\" on friendship between the two largest states of Asia; his vision of an internationalist foreign policy governed by the ethics of the Panchsheel ([[Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence]]), which he initially believed was shared by China. Nehru was disappointed when it became clear that the two countries had a conflict of interest in Tibet, which had traditionally served as a [[buffer zone]], and where India believed it had inherited special privileges from the [[British Raj]].\n\n===1950s===\n[[File:Prime Minister Nehru and Chinese Chairman Mao Zedong in Beijing.jpg|thumb|244px|Chairman [[Mao Zedong]] of China and Prime Minister [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] of India, during the former's state visit to China, October 1954.]]\nIndia [[Dates of establishment of diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China|established diplomatic relations with the PRC]] on 1 April 1950, the first non-communist nation in Asia to do so.\n\n[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] [[Chairman of the Communist Party of China|Chairman]] [[Mao Zedong]] viewed [[Tibet]] as an integral part of the People's Republic of China. The preceding government of the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] under [[Chiang Kai-shek]] also [[Tibet Area (administrative division)|claimed Tibet as Chinese territory]], however was unable to re-assert control. Chairman Mao saw Indian concern over Tibet as a manifestation of interference in the internal affairs of the PRC. The PRC reasserted control over [[Tibet (1912\u20131951)|Tibet]] and to end [[Lamaism]] (Tibetan Buddhism) and [[feudalism]], which it did by force of arms in 1950. To avoid antagonizing the PRC, Nehru informed Chinese leaders that India had no political ambitions or territorial ambitions and did not seek special privileges in Tibet but that traditional trading rights must continue. With Indian support, Tibetan delegates signed an agreement in May 1951 recognizing PRC sovereignty but guaranteeing that the existing political and social system of Tibet would continue.\n[[File:1952-06 1952\u5e745\u670816\u65e5\u4e2d\u5370\u53cb\u597d\u534f\u4f1a\u6210\u7acb.png|thumb|250px|right|Founding of the Sino-Indian Friendship Association on 16 May 1952 in Beijing.]]\n\nIn April 1954, India and the PRC signed an eight-year agreement on Tibet that became the [[Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence]] (or ''Panchsheel''). Although critics called the Panchsheel naive, Nehru calculated that India's best guarantee of security was to establish a psychological buffer zone in place of the lost physical buffer of Tibet.{{Citation needed|reason=source needed to support this claim of Nehru's reason for action|date=November 2018}}\n\nIt is the popular perception that the catchphrase of India's diplomacy with China in the 1950s was ''Hindi-Chini bhai-bhai'', which means, in [[Hindi]], \"Indians and Chinese are brothers\". While [[VK Krishna Menon]] was the Defence Minister in 1958, Nehru had privately told G. Parthasarathi the Indian envoy to China to send all communications directly to him, bypassing Menon, because of his communist background and sympathy towards China.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dont-believe-in-hindichini-bhaibhai-nehr/570332/ |title=Don't believe in Hindi-Chini bhai-bhai, Nehru told envoy |newspaper=Indian Express |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305124336/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dont-believe-in-hindichini-bhaibhai-nehr/570332/ |archivedate=5 March 2011  }}</ref>\n\nNehru sought to initiate a more direct dialogue between the peoples of China and India in culture and literature. Around then, the famous Indian artist (painter) [[Beohar Rammanohar Sinha]], who had earlier decorated the pages of the original [[Constitution of India]], was sent to China in 1957 on a Government of India fellowship to establish a direct cross-cultural and inter-civilization bridge. Noted Indian scholar [[Rahul Sankrityayan]] and diplomat [[Natwar Singh]] were also there, and [[Sarvapalli Radhakrishnan]] paid a visit to PRC. Between 1957 and 1959, [[Beohar Rammanohar Sinha]] not only disseminated Indian art in PRC but also became skilled in Chinese painting and lacquer-work. He also spent time with great masters [[Qi Baishi]], [[Li Keran]], [[Li Kuchan]] as well as some moments with Chairman [[Mao Zedong]] and Premier [[Zhou Enlai]]. Consequently, up until 1959, despite border skirmishes, Chinese leaders amicably had assured India that there was no territorial controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp?newsid=1101845|title='China, India and the fruits of Nehru's folly'|date=6 June 2007|work=dna|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090319030809/http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp?newsid=1101845|archivedate=19 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, India published new maps that included the [[Aksai Chin]] region within the boundaries of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl2120/stories/20041008000307600.htm|title=Nehru's legacy to India|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> When India discovered that China built a road through the region, border clashes and Indian protests became more frequent. In January 1959, PRC premier [[Zhou Enlai]] wrote to Nehru, pointing out that no government in China had accepted as legal the [[McMahon Line]], which the 1914 [[Simla Convention]] defined the eastern section of the border between India and Tibet.\n\nIn March 1959, the [[Dalai Lama]], spiritual and temporal head of the [[History of Tibet (1950\u2013present)|Tibet]], sought sanctuary in [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharmsala]], [[Himachal Pradesh]] where he established the [[Tibetan government-in-exile|Tibetan Government-in-Exile]]. Thousands of Tibetan refugees settled in northwestern India. The PRC accused India of [[expansionism]] and [[imperialism]] in Tibet and throughout the Himalayan region. China claimed 104,000&nbsp;km\u00b2 of territory over which India's maps showed clear sovereignty, and demanded \"rectification\" of the entire border.\n\n===1960s===\n{{Main|Sino-Indian War}}\n[[File:India disputed areas map.svg|thumb|Map showing [[List of disputed territories of India|disputed territories of India]]]]\nBorder disputes resulted in a short border war between the People's Republic of China and India on 20 October 1962.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book |last = Maxwell |first = Neville  |year = 2015 |title = India's China War (2nd Ed) |publisher = Natraj Publishers in Association with Wildlife Protection Society of India| location = New Delhi |isbn = 978-8181582508 |ref = none}}</ref>{{page needed|date=September 2017}} The border clash resulted in a defeat of India as the PRC pushed the Indian forces to within 48 km of the [[Assam]] plains in the northeast. It also occupied strategic points in the [[Aksai Chin]] and Demchok regions of [[Ladakh]], before declaring a unilateral [[ceasefire]] on 21 November. It claimed that it withdrew to 20 km behind its contended line of control. India disagreed with the claim.\n\nDuring the Sino-Indian border conflict, the India's [[Communist Party of India|Communist Party]] was accused by the Indian government of being pro-PRC, and many of its political leaders were jailed. Subsequently, the Communist Party of India (CPI) split with the leftist section{{Clarify|reason=It is not clear what is meant by the \"leftist section\"|date=April 2018}} forming the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] in 1964. CPI(M) held some contacts with the [[Communist Party of China]] for some time after the split but did not fully embrace the political line of Mao Zedong.\n\nRelations between the PRC and India deteriorated during the rest of the 1960s and the early 1970s while the [[China\u2013Pakistan relations]] improved and [[Sino-Soviet split|Sino-Soviet relations worsened]]. The PRC backed Pakistan in its [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965|1965 war with India]]. Between 1967 and 1971, an all-weather road was built across territory claimed by India, linking PRC's [[Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region]] with Pakistan; India could do no more than protest.\n\nThe PRC continued an active propaganda campaign against India and supplied ideological, financial and other assistance to dissident groups, especially to [[Tribes of India|tribe]]s in northeastern India. The PRC accused India of assisting the [[Kham]]pa rebels in Tibet.\n\nSri Lanka played the role of chief negotiator for the withdrawal of Chinese troops from the Indian territory. Both countries agreed to Colombo's proposals.<ref>The Foreign Policy of Sirimavo Bandaranaike - THE COLOMBO POWERS AND THE SINO-INDIAN WAR OF 1962</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Nathu La incident}}\n\n====Later conflicts====\n{{Main|1967 Nathu La and Cho La clashes| 1987 Sino-Indian skirmish}}\nIn late 1967, there were two more conflicts between Indian and Chinese forces at their contested border, in Sikkim. The first conflict was dubbed the \"Nathu La Incident\", and the other the \"Cho La Incident\".\n[[File:1967-09 1967\u5e74 \u5317\u4eac\u4e3e\u884c\u6297\u8bae\u5370\u5ea6\u7684\u793a\u5a01\u6e38\u884c.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Chinese demonstrations against Indian \"[[reactionary|reactionary factions]]\" in [[Beijing]] in 1967.]]\nIn September 1967, Chinese and Indian forces clashed at [[Nathu La]]. On 11 September, Chinese troops opened fire on a detachment of Indian soldiers tasked with protecting an engineering company that was fencing the North Shoulder of Nathu La. This escalated over the next five days to an exchange of heavy artillery and mortar fire between the Indian and Chinese forces. Sixty-two Indian soldiers were killed.<ref name=\"Amar Jawan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amar-jawan.org/querypage.asp?forceid=1|title=www.amar-jawan.org/querypage.asp?forceid=1|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607130752/http://www.amar-jawan.org/querypage.asp?forceid=1|archivedate=7 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nSoon afterwards, Indian and Chinese forces clashed again in the [[Chola incident]]. On 1 October 1967, some Indian and Chinese soldiers had an argument over the control of a boulder at the Chola outpost in [[Sikkim]] (then a [[protectorate]] of India), triggering a fight that escalated to a [[mortar (weapon)|mortar]] and [[heavy machine gun]] duel.<ref name=\"Chola\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/LAND-FORCES/Army/History/1960s/Chola.html|title=www.bharat-rakshak.com/LAND-FORCES/Army/History/1960s/Chola.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070525032355/http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/LAND-FORCES/Army/History/1960s/Chola.html|archivedate=25 May 2007}}</ref> On 10 October, both sides again exchanged heavy fire. While Indian forces would sustain eighty-eight troops killed in action with another 163 troops wounded, China would suffer less casualties, with 32 killed and 91 wounded in [[Nathu La]], as well as forty in Chola.<ref>\"Rapprochement Across the Himalayas: Emerging India-China Relations Post Cold\"{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pSpncRn2YFYC |title=Rapprochement Across the Himalayas: Emerging India-China Relations Post Cold War Period (1947-2003) |accessdate=15 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106003728/https://books.google.com/books?id=pSpncRn2YFYC |archivedate=6 January 2016  |isbn=9788178352947 |last1=Mishra |first1=Keshav |year=2004 }} p. 40</ref>\n\n===1970s===\nIn August 1971, India signed its [[Indo-Soviet Treaty of Friendship and Cooperation|Treaty of Peace, Friendship, and Co-operation]] with the [[Soviet Union]]. The PRC sided with Pakistan in its [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971|December 1971 war with India]]. Although China strongly condemned India, it did not carry out its veiled threat to intervene on Pakistan's behalf. By this time, the PRC had [[China and the United Nations|replaced the Republic of China in the UN]] where its representatives denounced India as being a \"tool of Soviet expansionism.\"\n\nIndia and the PRC renewed efforts to improve relations after Indian Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]]'s [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] lost the 1977 elections to [[Morarji Desai]]'s [[Janata Party]]. In 1978, the Indian Minister of External Affairs [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] made a landmark visit to Beijing, and both countries officially re-established diplomatic relations in 1979. The PRC modified its pro-Pakistan stand on [[Kashmir]] and appeared willing to remain silent on India's absorption of Sikkim and its special advisory relationship with [[Bhutan]]. The PRC's leaders agreed to discuss the boundary issue, India's priority, as the first step to a broadening of relations. The two countries hosted each other's news agencies, and [[Mount Kailash]] and [[Lake Manasarovar|Mansarowar Lake]] in Tibet, the home of the [[Hindu pantheon]], were opened to annual [[pilgrimage]]s.\n\n===1980s===\nIn 1981, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China, [[Huang Hua (politician)|Huang Hua]] made a landmark visit to New Delhi.<ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/huang-hua-diplomat-who-helped-thaw-ties-with-india-passes-away/article913255.ece|title=Huang Hua, diplomat who helped thaw ties with India, passes away|author=Ananth Krishnan|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109141426/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/huang-hua-diplomat-who-helped-thaw-ties-with-india-passes-away/article913255.ece|archivedate=9 January 2016|date=25 November 2010}}</ref> PRC Premier [[Zhao Ziyang]] concurrently toured [[Pakistan]], [[Nepal]], and [[Bangladesh]].\n\nIn 1980, Indian Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]] approved a plan to upgrade the deployment of forces around the Line of Actual Control. India also undertook infrastructural development in disputed areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1903/19030740.htm|title=Military common sense|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317092702/http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1903/19030740.htm|archivedate=17 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Sundarji\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatodaygroup.com/itoday/18051998/cover.html |title=www.indiatodaygroup.com/itoday/18051998/cover.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602213750/http://www.indiatodaygroup.com/itoday/18051998/cover.html |archivedate=2 June 2008  }}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, squads of Indian soldiers began actively patrolling the [[Sumdorong Chu]] Valley in [[Arunachal Pradesh]]. In the winter of 1986, the Chinese deployed their troops to the Sumdorong Chu before the Indian team could arrive and built a Helipad at Wandung.<ref>[http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/apr172005/spotlight942292005416.asp India's Land of the Rising Sun] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051231125701/http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/apr172005/spotlight942292005416.asp |date=31 December 2005 }} ''Deccan Herald''</ref> Surprised by the Chinese occupation, India's then Chief of Army Staff, [[Sundarji|General K.Sundarji]], airlifted a brigade to the region.<ref name=\"Sundarji\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.india-today.com/itoday/22021999/obit.html|title=Obituary: Warrior as Scholar: Gen (retd) K Sundarji (1928-1999)|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924204131/http://www.india-today.com/itoday/22021999/obit.html|archivedate=24 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nChinese troops could not move any further into the valley and were forced to away from the valley.<ref name=\"BS Mallik\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/sep03/edst.asp|title=www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/sep03/edst.asp|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050223021909/http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/sep03/edst.asp|archivedate=23 February 2005}}</ref> By 1987, Beijing's reaction was similar to that in 1962 and this prompted many Western diplomats to predict war. However, Indian foreign minister N.D. Tiwari and Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] travelled to Beijing to negotiate a mutual de-escalation.<ref name=\"Sundarji\"/>\n\nIndia and the PRC held eight rounds of border negotiations between December 1981 and November 1987. In 1985 the PRC insisted on mutual concessions without defining the exact terms of its \"package proposal\" or where the actual line of control lay. In 1986 and 1987, the negotiations achieved nothing, given the charges exchanged between the two countries of military encroachment in the [[Sumdorung Chu Valley]]. China's construction of a military post and helicopter pad in the area in 1986 and India's grant of statehood to [[Arunachal Pradesh]] (formerly the [[North-East Frontier Agency]]) in February 1987 caused both sides to deploy troops to the area. The PRC relayed warnings that it would \"teach India a lesson\" if it did not cease \"nibbling\" at Chinese territory. By the summer of 1987, however, both sides had backed away from conflict and denied military clashes had taken place.\n\nA warming trend in relations was facilitated by [[Rajiv Gandhi]]'s visit to China in December 1988. The two sides issued a joint communiqu\u00e9 that stressed the need to restore friendly relations on the basis of the Panchsheel. India and the People's Republic of China agreed to achieve a \"fair and reasonable settlement while seeking a mutually acceptable solution\" to the border dispute. The communiqu\u00e9 also expressed China's concern about agitation by [[Tibetan separatism|Tibetan separatists]] in India and reiterated that anti-China political activities by expatriate Tibetans would not be tolerated. Rajiv Gandhi signed bilateral agreements on science and technology co-operation, establish direct air links, and on cultural exchanges. The two sides also agreed to hold annual diplomatic consultations between foreign ministers, set up a joint committee on economic and scientific co-operation, and a joint working group on the boundary issue. The latter group was to be led by the Indian foreign secretary and the Chinese vice minister of foreign affairs.\n\n===1990s===\nTop-level dialogue continued with the December 1991 visit of [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|PRC premier]] [[Li Peng]] to India and the May 1992 visit to China of [[president of India|Indian president]] [[R. Venkataraman]]. Six rounds of talks of the Indian-Chinese Joint Working Group on the Border Issue were held between December 1988 and June 1993. Progress was also made in reducing tensions on the border via mutual troop reductions, regular meetings of local military commanders, and advance notification about military exercises. In July 1992, [[Sharad Pawar]] visited [[Beijing]], the first Indian Minister of Defence to do so. Consulates reopened in [[Bombay]] (Mumbai) and [[Shanghai]] in December 1992.\n\nIn 1993, The sixth-round of the joint working group talks was held in [[New Delhi]] but resulted in only minor developments. Prime Minister [[Narasimha Rao]] and Premier Li Peng signed a border agreement dealing with cross-border trade, cooperation on environmental issues (e.g. [[Pollution]], [[Endangered Species|Animal extinction]], [[Global Warming]], etc.) and radio and television broadcasting. A senior-level Chinese military delegation made a goodwill visit to India in December 1993 aimed at \"fostering confidence-building measures between the defence forces of the two countries.\" The visit, however, came at a time when China was providing greater military support to Burma. The presence of Chinese radar technicians in Burma's [[Coco Islands]], which border India's [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]] caused concern in India.\n\nIn January 1994, Beijing announced that it not only favored a negotiated solution on Kashmir, but also opposed any form of independence for the region. Talks were held in New Delhi in February aimed at confirming established \"confidence-building measures\", discussing clarification of the \"line of actual control\", reduction of armed forces along the line, and prior information about forthcoming military exercises. China's hope for settlement of the boundary issue was reiterated.\n\nIn 1995, talks by the India-China Expert Group led to an agreement to set up two additional points of contact along the 4,000&nbsp;km border to facilitate meetings between military personnel. The two sides were reportedly \"seriously engaged\" in defining the McMahon Line and the line of actual control vis-\u00e0-vis military exercises and prevention of air intrusion. Talks were held in Beijing in July and in New Delhi in August to improve border security, combat cross-border crimes and on additional troop withdrawals from the border. These talks further reduced tensions.<ref>\nLin Liangguang Ye Zhengjia and Han Hua, Contemporary China\u2019s Relations with South Asia Countries, Beijing: Social Sciences Documentation Publishing House 2001.</ref>\n\nThere was little notice taken in Beijing of the April 1995 announcement of the opening of the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Centre]] in New Delhi. The Centre serves as the representative office of the [[Republic of China]] (Taiwan) and is the counterpart of the [[India-Taipei Association]] located in Taiwan. Both institutions share the goal of improving India-ROC relations, which have been strained since New Delhi's recognition of Beijing in 1950.\n\nSino-Indian relations hit a low point in 1998 following India's [[nuclear test]]s. Indian Defence Minister [[George Fernandes]] declared that \"\u201cin my perception of national security, China is enemy No 1.\u2026and any person who is concerned about India\u2019s security must agree with that fact\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/week-asia/geopolitics/article/2104017/why-china-so-keen-alienate-half-billion-young-indians-no|title=Why is China alienating half a billion young Indians?|website=scmp.com|accessdate=27 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725145210/http://www.scmp.com/week-asia/geopolitics/article/2104017/why-china-so-keen-alienate-half-billion-young-indians-no|archivedate=25 July 2017|date=25 July 2017}}</ref> hinting that India developed nuclear weapons in defence against China's nuclear arsenal. In 1998, China was one of the strongest international critics of India's nuclear tests and entry into the nuclear club. During the 1999 [[Kargil War]] China voiced support for Pakistan, but also counseled Pakistan to withdraw its forces.\n\n===2000s===\n[[File:Officers at Nathu La.JPG|thumb|Indian and Chinese officers at [[Nathu La]]. Nathu La was re-opened in 2006 following numerous bilateral trade agreements. The opening of the pass is expected to bolster the economy of the region and play a key role in the growing Sino-Indian trade.]]\nIn a major embarrassment for China, the 17th [[Karmapa]], [[Urgyen Trinley Dorje]], who was proclaimed by China, made a dramatic escape from Tibet to the [[Rumtek Monastery]] in Sikkim. Chinese officials were in a quandary on this issue as any protest to India on the issue would mean an explicit endorsement on India's governance of Sikkim, which the Chinese still hadn't recognised. In 2003, China officially recognised Indian sovereignty over Sikkim as the two countries moved towards resolving their border disputes.\n\nIn 2004, the two countries proposed opening up the [[Nathula]] and [[Jelepla Pass]]es in Sikkim. 2004 was a milestone in Sino-Indian bilateral trade, surpassing the US$10 billion mark for the first time. In April 2005, Chinese Premier [[Wen Jiabao]] visited [[Bangalore]] to push for increased Sino-Indian cooperation in high-tech industries. Wen stated that the 21st century will be \"the Asian century of the IT industry.\"Regarding the issue of India gaining a permanent seat on the [[UN Security Council]], Wen Jiabao initially seemed to support the idea, but had returned to a neutral position.\n\nIn the [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]] (SAARC) Summit in 2005, China was granted an observer status. While other countries in the region are ready to consider China for permanent membership in the SAARC, India seemed reluctant.\n\nIssues surrounding energy has risen in significance. Both countries have growing energy demand to support economic growth. Both countries signed an agreement in 2006 to envisage [[ONGC]] Videsh Ltd (OVL) and the [[China National Petroleum Corporation]] (CNPC) to placing joint bids for promising projects.\n\nIn 2006, China and India re-opened [[Nathula]] pass for trading. Nathula was closed 44 years prior to 2006. Re-opening of border trade will help ease the economic isolation of the region.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5093712.stm \"India-China trade link to reopen\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621055444/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5093712.stm |date=21 June 2006 }}, BBC News, 19 June 2006. Retrieved 31 January 2007.</ref> In November 2006, China and India had a verbal spat over claim of the north-east Indian state of [[Arunachal Pradesh]]. India claimed that China was occupying 38,000 square kilometres of its territory in [[Kashmir]], while China claimed the whole of Arunachal Pradesh as its own.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6145866.stm \"India and China row over border\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215103833/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6145866.stm |date=15 February 2008 }}, BBC News, 14 November 2006. Retrieved 31 January 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, China denied the application for visa from an [[Indian Administrative Service]] officer in Arunachal Pradesh. According to China, since Arunachal Pradesh is a territory of China, he would not need a visa to visit his own country.<ref name=\"IBN-IAS\">{{cite news |title=China denies visa to IAS officer |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/china-denies-visa-to-ias-officer/41328-3.html |publisher=CNN-IBN |date=25 May 2007 |accessdate=31 August 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821192016/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/china-denies-visa-to-ias-officer/41328-3.html |archivedate=21 August 2007  }}</ref> Later in December 2007, China reversed its policy by granting a visa to Marpe Sora, an Arunachal born professor in computer science.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7132636.stm|title=BBC NEWS - South Asia - Chinese 'border gesture' to India|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718211146/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7132636.stm|archivedate=18 July 2016|date=7 December 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2007-12-09/india/27989328_1_marpe-sora-chinese-visa-arunachalee|title=A thaw? China lets Arunachalee visit|work=The Times of India|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\nIn January 2008, Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] visited China to discuss trade, commerce, defence, military, and various other issues.\n\nUntil 2008 the British Government's position remained the same as had been since the [[Simla Accord (1914)|Simla Accord]] of 1913: that China held [[suzerainty]] over Tibet but not [[sovereignty]]. Britain revised this view on 29 October 2008, when it recognized Chinese sovereignty over Tibet through its website.<ref>[[David Miliband]], [http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/newsroom/latest-news/?view=PressS&id=8299838 Written Ministerial Statement on Tibet (29/10/2008)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202021442/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/newsroom/latest-news/?view=PressS&id=8299838 |date=2 December 2008 }}'', Foreign Office website, Retrieved 25 November 2008.''</ref><ref>Richard Spencer, ''[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/tibet/3385803/UK-recognises-Chinas-direct-rule-over-Tibet.html UK recognises China's direct rule over Tibet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103224606/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/tibet/3385803/UK-recognises-Chinas-direct-rule-over-Tibet.html |date=3 November 2010 }}'', [[The Daily Telegraph]], 5 November 2008</ref><ref>Shai Oster, ''[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122549900302589905?mod=googlenews_wsj U.K. Policy Angers Tibet Ahead of Beijing Talks]'', [[The Wall Street Journal]], 1 November 2008</ref> [[The Economist]] stated that although the British Foreign Office's website does not use the word sovereignty, officials at the Foreign Office said \"it means that, as far as Britain is concerned, 'Tibet is part of China. Full stop.'\"<ref>Staff, ''[http://www.economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12570571 Britain's suzerain remedy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210165838/http://www.economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12570571 |date=10 December 2008 }}'', [[The Economist]], 6 November 2008</ref> This change in Britain's position affects India's claim to its North Eastern territories which rely on the same Simla Accord that Britain's prior position on Tibet's sovereignty was based upon.<ref>Robert Barnett, ''[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/25/opinion/25barnett.html?_r=1&ref=opinion Did Britain Just Sell Tibet?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150105005512/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/25/opinion/25barnett.html?_r=1&ref=opinion |date=5 January 2015 }}'', [[The New York Times]], 24 November 2008</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, [[Asian Development Bank]] formally acknowledging Arunachal Pradesh as part of India, approved a loan to India for a development project there. Earlier China had exercised pressure on the bank to cease the loan,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adb.org/projects/project.asp?id=42192 |title=Project Records &#124; Asian Development Bank |publisher=Adb.org |date=11 September 2008 |accessdate=3 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424055142/http://www2.adb.org/projects/project.asp?id=42192 |archivedate=24 April 2012  }}</ref> however India succeeded in securing the loan with the help of the United States and Japan. China expressed displeasure at [[Asian Development Bank|ADB]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/nation/article92904.ece|title=China objected to ADB loan to India|date=9 July 2009|publisher=The New Indian Express|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106091607/http://newindianexpress.com/nation/article92904.ece|archivedate=6 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/uncategorized/china-objected-to-adb-loan-to-india-for-arunachal-project-krishna-lead_100215729.html|title=China objected to ADB loan to India for Arunachal project: Krishna (Lead) - Thaindian News|date=9 July 2009|publisher=Thaindian.com|accessdate=3 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007035211/http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/uncategorized/china-objected-to-adb-loan-to-india-for-arunachal-project-krishna-lead_100215729.html|archivedate=7 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nA public opinion poll of the entire population of China conducted by Pew in spring 2008 shows:\n: Views toward Japan are especially negative \u2013 69% have an unfavorable opinion of Japan, and a significant number of Chinese (38%) consider Japan an enemy. Opinions of the United States also tend to be negative, and 34% describe the U.S. as an enemy, while just 13% say it is a partner of China. Views about India are mixed at best \u2013 25% say India is a partner, while a similar number (24%) describe it as an enemy.<ref> ''The 2008 Pew Global Attitudes Survey in China'' (22 July 2008)  p 5. [https://www.pewresearch.org/global/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2008/07/2008-Pew-Global-Attitudes-Report-2-July-22-2pm.pdf online] </ref>\n\n===2010s===\n\nChinese Premier [[Wen Jiabao]] paid an official visit to India from 15\u201317 December 2010 at the invitation of Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/7234845.html |title=Chinese premier urges closer cultural, youth links with India - People's Daily Online |publisher=English.peopledaily.com.cn |date=17 December 2010 |accessdate=3 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015130509/http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90776/90883/7234845.html |archivedate=15 October 2012  }}</ref>  He was accompanied by 400 Chinese business leaders, who wished to sign business deals with Indian companies.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11997221 | work=BBC News | title=Chinese PM Wen Jiabao begins bumper Indian trade trip | date=15 December 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126030456/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11997221 | archivedate=26 January 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{cquote|India and China are two very populous countries with ancient civilisations, friendship between the two countries has a time-honoured history, which can be dated back 2,000 years, and since the establishment of diplomatic ties between our two countries, in particular the last ten years, friendship and cooperation has made significant progress.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101216/main2.htm |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Main News |publisher=Tribuneindia.com |accessdate=2012-08-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102111044/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101216/main2.htm |archivedate=2 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><center><small>Premier [[Wen Jiabao]] at the [[Tagore International School]], 15 December 2010</small>}}\n\nIn April 2011, during the [[2011 BRICS summit|BRICS summit]] in [[Sanya]], [[Hainan]], China<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-13034172 | work=BBC News | title=Indian PM Manmohan Singh heads to China for talks | date=11 April 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412035312/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-13034172 | archivedate=12 April 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> the two countries agreed to restore defence co-operation and China had hinted that it may reverse its policy of administering stapled visas to residents of [[Jammu and Kashmir]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/visa-and-immigration/china-hints-at-scrapping-stapled-visa-for-j-and-k-people/articleshow/7970880.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=Nri | date=13 April 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418094702/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/visa-and-immigration/china-hints-at-scrapping-stapled-visa-for-j-and-k-people/articleshow/7970880.cms | archivedate=18 April 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/story/india-china-to-restore-defence-co-operation/1/135160.html |title=India, China to restore defence co-operation : Neighbours, News - India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=3 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110801173352/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/story/india-china-to-restore-defence-co-operation/1/135160.html |archivedate=1 August 2011  }}</ref>  This practice was later stopped,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com//articleshow/11217007.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=2011: India, China solve stapled visa issue; put off border talks | date=23 December 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314153435/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com//articleshow/11217007.cms | archivedate=14 March 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and as a result, defence ties were resumed between the two countries and joint military drills were expected.\n\nIt was reported in February 2012 that India will reach US$100 billion trade with China by 2015.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/foreign-trade/India-hopes-to-reach-100-billion-dollar-trade-with-China-by-2015-Krishna/articleshow/11813148.cms | work=Economic Times | title=India to reach US$100 billion dollar trade with China by 2015 | date=9 February 2012}}</ref> Bilateral trade between the two countries reached US$73 billion in 2011, making China India's largest trade partner, but slipped to US$66 billion in 2012.<ref name=R20>{{cite web|title=India Gripes Over Border, Trade Woes on Li's First Foreign Trip|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/100749094|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=20 May 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104193439/http://www.cnbc.com/id/100749094|archivedate=4 November 2013|date=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2012 BRICS summit]] in [[New Delhi]], India, Chinese President [[Hu Jintao]] told Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] that \"it is China's unswerving policy to develop Sino-Indian friendship, deepen strategic cooperation and seek common development\" and \"China hopes to see a peaceful, prosperous and continually developing India and is committed to building more dynamic China-India relationship\".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/china-wants-to-deepen-strategic-cooperation-with-india-hu-jintao/articleshow/12469429.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=China wants to deepen strategic cooperation with India: Hu Jintao | date=30 March 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314065809/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/china-wants-to-deepen-strategic-cooperation-with-india-hu-jintao/articleshow/12469429.cms | archivedate=14 March 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>  Other topics were discussed, including border dispute problems and a unified BRICS central bank.\n\nIn response to India's test of an [[Agni-V]] missile capable of carrying a nuclear warhead to Beijing, the PRC called for the two countries to \"cherish the hard-earned momentum of co-operation\".<ref>Nelson, Dean. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/9216554/China-warns-India-of-arrogance-over-missile-launch.html \"China warns India of arrogance over missile launch.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420155645/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/9216554/China-warns-India-of-arrogance-over-missile-launch.html |date=20 April 2012 }} ''The Telegraph''. 20 April 2012.</ref>\n\nA three-week [[2013 Daulat Beg Oldi Incident|standoff]] between Indian and Chinese troops in close proximity to each other and the [[Line of Actual Control]] between [[Jammu and Kashmir]]'s [[Ladakh]] region and [[Aksai Chin]] was defused on 5 May 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/05/06/us-india-china-idUSBRE9440B220130506|title=India says China agrees retreat to de facto border in faceoff deal|author=Reuters Editorial|date=6 May 2013|work=Reuters|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924181040/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/05/06/us-india-china-idUSBRE9440B220130506|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref> days before a trip by Indian Foreign Minister [[Salman Khurshid]] to China; Khurshid said that both countries had a shared interest in not having the border issue exacerbate or \"destroy\" long-term progress in relations. The Chinese agreed to withdraw their troops in exchange for an Indian agreement to demolish several \"live-in bunkers\" 250&nbsp;km to the south in the disputed Chumar sector.<ref>Defence News. [http://www.defencenews.in/defence-news-internal.asp?get=new&id=1554 \"India Destroyed Bunkers in Chumar to Resolve Ladakh Row\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724185744/http://defencenews.in/defence-news-internal.asp?get=new&id=1554 |date=24 July 2013 }}. ''Defence News''. 8 May 2013. Retrieved 11 May 2013.</ref>\n\n[[File:BRICS leaders meet on the sidelines of 2016 G20 Summit in China.jpg|thumb|250 px|The [[BRICS]] [[List of BRICS summit attendees|leaders]] in China, 2016]]\nChinese Premier [[Li Keqiang]] made his first foreign visit to India on 18 May 2013 in a bid to increase diplomatic co-operation, to cement trade relations, and formulate border dispute solutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/05/201351972251986773.html|title=Chinese premier visits India|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314021927/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/05/201351972251986773.html|archivedate=14 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mea.gov.in/bilateral-documents.htm?dtl/21723/Joint+Statement+on+the+State+Visit+of+Chinese++Li+Keqiang+to+India|title=Joint Statement on the State Visit of Chinese Premier Li Keqiang to India|publisher=[[Ministry of External Affairs (India)]]|date=20 May 2013|accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIndian President Pranab Mukherjee's visit to [[Arunachal Pradesh]], a northeast Indian state that China recognizes as \"South Tibet\",  in late November 2013 and in his speech calling the area an \"integral and important part of India\" generated an angry response from Beijing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2013/12/chinas-arunachal-pradesh-fixation/|title=China's Arunachal Pradesh Fixation|author1=Aakriti Bachhawat|author2=The Diplomat|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304235102/http://thediplomat.com/2013/12/chinas-arunachal-pradesh-fixation/|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Foreign ministry spokesman Qin Gang's statement in response to Mukherjee's two-day visit to Arunachal Pradesh was \"China's stance on the disputed area on the eastern part of the China-India border is consistent and clear.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/China-reiterates-claim-on-Arunachal-Pradesh-through-mouthpiece/articleshow/26644947.cms?referral=PM|title=China reiterates claim on Arunachal Pradesh through mouthpiece - The Times of India|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903225941/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/China-reiterates-claim-on-Arunachal-Pradesh-through-mouthpiece/articleshow/26644947.cms?referral=PM|archivedate=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014 the relationship took a sting as troops of the People's Liberation Army (PLA) have reportedly entered two kilometres inside the Line of Actual Control (LAC) in Chumar sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/chinese-troops-said-to-be-2-km-inside-lac-build-up-on-the-rise/|title=Chinese troops said to be 2 km inside LAC, build-up on the rise|date=23 September 2014|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305160702/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/chinese-troops-said-to-be-2-km-inside-lac-build-up-on-the-rise/|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> The next month, [[V. K. Singh]] said that China and India had come to a \"convergence of views\" on the threat of terrorism emanating from Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/afghanistan-meet-china-india-pakistan-terror-concerns-border-taliban-terrorism/1/398565.html |title=Delhi, Kabul warn China: Pak maybe your ally but it exports terror |last1=Krishnan |first1=Ananth |date=31 October 2014 |website=intoday.in |publisher=Living Media India Limited |accessdate=1 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101124724/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/afghanistan-meet-china-india-pakistan-terror-concerns-border-taliban-terrorism/1/398565.html |archivedate=1 November 2014  }}</ref>\n\nIn more modern times, China and India have been working together to produce films together, such as ''[[Kung Fu Yoga]]'' starring [[Jackie Chan]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/jackie-chan-pair-for-golden-network-1201632878/|title= AFM: Golden Network Kicks Off With Jackie Chan Movie Pair|author= Patrick Frater|date= 4 November 2015|accessdate= 1 November 2016|work= [[variety.com]]|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170202063731/http://variety.com/2015/film/asia/jackie-chan-pair-for-golden-network-1201632878/|archivedate= 2 February 2017|df= dmy-all}}</ref> However, disruptions have risen again due to China building trade routes with Pakistan on disputed Kashmir territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/india-to-boycott-china-summit-amid-kashmir-concerns-8844892|title=India to boycott China summit amid Kashmir concerns|website=channelnewsasia.com|accessdate=27 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516170650/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/india-to-boycott-china-summit-amid-kashmir-concerns-8844892|archivedate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, India reiterated that it would not join China's [[Belt and Road Initiative]], stating that it cannot accept a project that ignores concerns about its territorial integrity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/india-wont-join-bri-its-concept-wont-apply-to-us-jaishankar20191004161140/|title=India won't join BRI, its concept won't apply to us: Jaishankar|last=|first=|date=4 October 2019|work=[[Asian News International]]|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> \n\n==== 2017 Doklam standoff ====\n{{main|2017 China\u2013India border standoff}}\nOn 16 June 2017 Chinese troops with construction vehicles and road-building equipment began extending an existing road southward in [[Doklam]], a territory which is claimed by both [[China]] as well as [[India]]'s ally [[Bhutan]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.bt/press-releases/press-release-272.html|title=Press Release \u2013 Ministry of Foreign Affairs|website=www.mfa.gov.bt|access-date=20 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630023420/http://www.mfa.gov.bt/press-releases/press-release-272.html|archive-date=30 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfn|China Foreign Ministry|2017|p=6}}<ref name=\"Barry\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/26/world/asia/dolam-plateau-china-india-bhutan.html|title=How India and China Have Come to the Brink Over a Remote Mountain Pass|last=Barry|first=Steven Lee Myers, Ellen|date=26 July 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 August 2017|last2=Fisher|first2=Max|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-india-idUSKBN19O109|title=China says India violates 1890 agreement in border stand-off|date=3 July 2017|work=Reuters|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/06/china-india-bhutan-standoff-disputed-territory|title=Chinese and Indian troops face off in Bhutan border dispute|first=Michael|last=Safi|date=5 July 2017|publisher=|accessdate=10 August 2017|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-china-india-doklam-standoff-20170724-story.html |title=Doklam standoff: China sends a warning to India over border dispute |access-date=11 August 2017 |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |date=24 July 2017}}</ref> On 18 June 2017, around 270 Indian troops, with weapons and two bulldozers, entered Doklam to stop the Chinese troops from constructing the road.<ref name=\"Barry\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-india-idUSKBN19O109|title=China says India violates 1890 agreement in border stand-off|date=3 July 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=16 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/06/china-india-bhutan-standoff-disputed-territory|title=Chinese and Indian troops face off in Bhutan border dispute|last=Safi|first=Michael|date=5 July 2017|publisher=|accessdate=10 August 2017|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://accesswdun.com/article/2017/8/566782|title=China warns Indian troops to get out of contested region|publisher=|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref>\nAmong other charges, China accused India of illegal intrusion into its territory, across what it called the mutually agreed China-India boundary, and violation of its territorial sovereignty and UN Charter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/wjdt_665385/2649_665393/P020170802542676636134.pdf|title=The Facts and China's Position Concerning the Indian Border Troops' Crossing of the China-India Boundary in the Sikkim Sector into the Chinese Territory (2017-08-02)|last=China Foreign Ministry|date=2 August 2017|website=www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/wjdt_665385/2649_665393/|access-date=15 August 2017}}</ref> India accused China of changing the status quo in violation of a 2012 understanding between the two governments regarding the tri-junction boundary points and causing \"security concerns\", which were widely understood as at its concerns with the strategic [[Siliguri Corridor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mea.gov.in/press-releases.htm?dtl/28572/Recent_Developments_in_Doklam_Area|title=Recent Developments in Doklam Area|website=mea.gov.in|access-date=17 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2017/07/whats-driving-the-india-china-standoff-at-doklam/|title=What's Driving the India-China Standoff at Doklam?|last=Diplomat|first=Ankit Panda, The|work=The Diplomat|access-date=17 August 2017}}</ref> India media reported that on 28 June Bhutan issued a ''demarche,'' demanding China to cease road-building in Doklam and maintain the status quo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/world/bhutan-issues-demarche-to-china-over-its-armys-road-construction-4726615/|title=Bhutan issues demarche to China over its army's road construction|date=28 June 2017|access-date=28 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729002236/http://indianexpress.com/article/world/bhutan-issues-demarche-to-china-over-its-armys-road-construction-4726615/|archivedate=29 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Minister of External Affairs of India [[Sushma Swaraj]] said that if China unilaterally changed the status-quo of the tri-junction point between China-India and Bhutan then it posed a challenge to the security of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/sushma-swaraj-rajya-sabha-bhutan-sikkim-china-india-doklam-standoff-4759229/|title=If China unilaterally changes status-quo in Doklam, it's a challenge to our security: Sushma Swaraj|date=20 July 2017|website=indianexpress.com|accessdate=27 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729010029/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/sushma-swaraj-rajya-sabha-bhutan-sikkim-china-india-doklam-standoff-4759229/|archivedate=29 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 July 2017, Chinese Foreign Minister [[Wang Yi (politician)|Wang Yi]] claimed that Chinese troops had not intruded into Indian territory by its own admission.<ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|last=CCTV\u4e2d\u6587\u56fd\u9645|title=[Focus Today] 20170726 {{!}} CCTV-4|date=25 July 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8KT9IX_xM14|accessdate=17 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">Wang Zihao, [https://www.ecns.cn/voices/2017/08-03/267944.shtml U.S. scholar: India should remember the history], [[China Daily]], 3 August 2017</ref>\nThe US expressed concern in mid July 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/sikkim-standoff-bhutan-china-india-global-times-4736437/|title=Sikkim standoff: Chinese media says India will suffer 'greater losses' than 1962 if it 'incites' border tensions|date=5 July 2017|work=The Indian Express|access-date=5 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705091509/http://indianexpress.com/article/india/sikkim-standoff-bhutan-china-india-global-times-4736437/|archivedate=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/chinese-media-ups-the-ante-asks-india-to-withdraw-from-dokalam-area-with-dignity/articleshow/59453251.cms|title=Withdraw with dignity or be kicked out, Chinese media threatens India|last=PTI|date=5 July 2017|work=The Economic Times|access-date=5 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706022731/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/chinese-media-ups-the-ante-asks-india-to-withdraw-from-dokalam-area-with-dignity/articleshow/59453251.cms|archivedate=6 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/china-may-have-quietly-moved-tonnes-war-gear-in-northern-tibet-claims-report/articleshow/59660926.cms|title=China may have quietly moved tonnes of war gear into northern Tibet, claims report|date=19 July 2017|work=The Economic Times|access-date=19 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/us-concerned-about-india-china-border-standoff-says-both-sides-should-work-together-for-peace/articleshow/59660462.cms|title=US 'concerned' about India-China border standoff, says 'both sides should work together' for peace - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=19 July 2017}}</ref> China repeatedly said that India's withdrawal was a prerequisite for meaningful dialogue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/doklam-stand-off-china-wants-india-to-retreat-for-meaningful-dialogue-117071000810_1.html|title=Doklam stand-off: China wants India to retreat for meaningful dialogue|last=ANI|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=27 July 2017|via=Business Standard|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729005142/http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/doklam-stand-off-china-wants-india-to-retreat-for-meaningful-dialogue-117071000810_1.html|archivedate=29 July 2017|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eldzpnD0QFQ|title=China urges India to withdraw troops from Chinese territory|last=CGTN|date=18 July 2017|publisher=|accessdate=27 July 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8SJGrLuamEw|title=China said India's withdrawal a prerequisite for meaningful dialogue|last=Rise of the India|date=20 July 2017|publisher=|accessdate=27 July 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref>  On 21 July 2017, the Minister of External Affairs of India [[Sushma Swaraj]] said that for dialogue, both India and China must withdraw their troops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/china-aiming-at-unilaterally-changing-tri-junction-status-sushma-swaraj/articleshow/59681474.cms|title=For dialogue, both India and China must withdraw troops, says Sushma Swaraj|first=Dipanjan Roy|last=Chaudhury|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=27 July 2017|via=The Economic Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729030245/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/china-aiming-at-unilaterally-changing-tri-junction-status-sushma-swaraj/articleshow/59681474.cms|archivedate=29 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2017, the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of China]] published a document entitled, ''\u5370\u5ea6\u8fb9\u9632\u90e8\u961f\u5728\u4e2d\u5370\u8fb9\u754c\u9521\u91d1\u6bb5\u8d8a\u754c \u8fdb\u5165\u4e2d\u56fd\u9886\u571f\u7684\u4e8b\u5b9e\u548c\u4e2d\u56fd\u7684\u7acb\u573a (Indian border forces cross the border between China and India...The facts...and the position of China)'', claiming that Indian border forces had illegally crossed the border between China and India and detailed China's position on the matter.<ref name=\"china_position\">{{cite web|title=\u5370\u5ea6\u8fb9\u9632\u90e8\u961f\u5728\u4e2d\u5370\u8fb9\u754c\u9521\u91d1\u6bb5\u8d8a\u754c \u8fdb\u5165\u4e2d\u56fd\u9886\u571f\u7684\u4e8b\u5b9e\u548c\u4e2d\u56fd\u7684\u7acb\u573a|url=http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/web/zyxw/P020170802541371281020.pdf|language=Chinese|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802164857/http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/web/zyxw/P020170802541371281020.pdf|archivedate=2 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/wjdt_665385/2649_665393/P020170802542676636134.pdf|title=The Facts and China's Position Concerning the Indian Border Troops' Crossing of the China-India Boundary in the Sikkim Sector into the Chinese Territory (2017-08-02)|last=|first=|date=2 August 2017|website=www.fmprc.gov.cn|access-date=12 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com//english/2017-08/02/c_136494051.htm|title=China issues position document on Indian border troop trespass - Xinhua &#124; English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com}}</ref><ref name=\"8_4_2017 border stand-off\">{{cite news|last1=Blanchard|first1=Ben|title=China says India building up troops amid border stand-off|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/china-says-india-building-troops-amid-border-stand-002422962.html|work=Reuters|agency=Yahoo|date=4 August 2017}}</ref> The document said that China notified India regarding its plan to construct road in advance \"in full reflection of China\u2019s goodwill\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Ministry of External Affairs, India|title=Weekly Media Briefing by Official Spokesperson (August 4, 2017)|date=4 August 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FJnAoru8VsY|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> The Indian Foreign Ministry replied by referring towards their earlier press release on this matter, as opposed to a point-by-point rebuttal.<ref>{{cite news |last1=TheWire |title=With the Release of an Official Document, China Ups the Ante Again on Doklam |url=https://thewire.in/diplomacy/china-doklam-document |work=The Wire |date=2 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 2017, China and India reached a consensus to put an end to the border stand-off. Both of them agreed to disengage from the standoff in Doklam.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/3051444f31557a6333566d54/share_p.html|title=China: India has withdrawn troops from Donglang and border standoff is over|access-date=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n==2018==\n\nIn May 2018, the two countries agreed to coordinate their development programmes in Afghanistan in the areas of health, education and food security.<ref>[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-china-likely-to-jointly-undertake-projects-in-afghanistan/articleshow/64057491.cms India, China likely to jointly undertake projects in Afghanistan], ''The Economic Times'', 7 May 2018.</ref><br/>On 11 October 2019, Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]] met with Indian prime minister [[Narendra Modi]] at [[Mahabalipuram]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]] for a second informal meeting between India and China.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==== 2019 ====\nIt has been finalized that in 2020, on the 70th anniversary of India-China diplomatic ties, 70 events will be held in celebration. Various other activities are also planned.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Bilateral trade==\nChina is India's [[List of the largest trading partners of India|largest trading partner]].\n\nChinese imports from India amounted to $16.4 billion or 0.8% of its overall imports, and 4.2% of India's overall exports in 2014. The 10 major commodities exported from India to China were:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top_china_imports.html|title=Top China Imports|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516091700/http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top_china_imports.html|archivedate=16 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"worldsrichestcountries.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top_china_exports.html|title=Top China Exports|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521174632/http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top_china_exports.html|archivedate=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n#Cotton: $3.2 billion\n#Gems, precious metals, coins: $2.5 billion\n#Copper: $2.3 billion\n#Ores, slag, ash: $1.3 billion\n#Organic chemicals: $1.1 billion\n#Salt, sulphur, stone, cement: $958.7 million\n#Machines, engines, pumps: $639.7lmillion\n#Plastics: $499.7 million\n#Electronic equipment: $440 million\n#Raw hides excluding furskins: $432.7 million\n\nChinese exports to India amounted to $58.4 billion or 2.3% of its overall exports, and 12.6% of India's overall imports in 2014. The 10 major commodities exported from China to India were:<ref name=\"worldsrichestcountries.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top-india-imports.html|title=Top India Imports|accessdate=16 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503112643/http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top-india-imports.html|archivedate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n#Electronic equipment: $16 billion\n#Machines, engines, pumps: $9.8 billion\n#Organic chemicals: $6.3 billion\n#Fertilizers: $2.7 billion\n#Iron and steel: $2.3 billion\n#Plastics: $1.7 billion\n#Iron or steel products: $1.4 billion\n#Gems, precious metals, coins: $1.3 billion\n#Ships, boats: $1.3 billion\n#Medical, technical equipment: $1.2 billion\n\n==See also==\n\" PICFA\" Pondicherry India China friendship association : Non- government organisation in India , dedicated in developing people to people relation between India and China in the areas of education ,culture ,trade and tourism .( www.picfa.in{{Portal|China|India|Politics}}\n\n===Sino-Indian relations===\n*[[Chindian]] People of mixed Indian and Chinese ancestry\n*[[BRICS]] &ndash; Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa\n*[[China in the Mahabharata]]\n*[[Chindia]] &ndash; China and India together in general, and their economies in particular\n*[[Shanghai Co-operation Organisation]]\n* [[Bhutan\u2013China relations]]\n* [[Bhutan\u2013India relations]]\n\n===Border disputes===\n*[[Sino-Indian border dispute]] \n*[[Aksai Chin]] &ndash; controlled by China and claimed by India.\n*[[Arunachal Pradesh]] &ndash; controlled by India and claimed by China. Inhabited by [[Moinba]]s, [[Lhoba]]s (Adi), and [[Mishmi people|Daibamei]]s.\n*[[Doklam]]\n*[[Tawang District]] &ndash; controlled by India and claimed by China.\n*[[Trans-Karakoram Tract#Shaksgam Valley|Shaksgam Valley]] &ndash; controlled by China and claimed by India (Conferred to China in 1963 by Pakistan) [[Trans-Karakoram Tract]].\n* [[Bhutan\u2013China border]]\n* [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea]]\n*[[List of territorial disputes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin|30em}} \n*Bagchi, Prabodh Chandra, Bangwei Wang, and Tansen Sen. 2012. ''India and China: interactions through Buddhism and diplomacy : a collection of essays by Professor Prabodh Chandra Bagchi''. Singapore: ISEAS Pub. \n*Bhat, R. B., & Wu, C. (2014). ''Xuan Zhang's mission to the West with Monkey King''. New Delhi : Aditya Prakashan, 2014.\n*[[Lokesh Chandra|Chandra, Lokesh]]. 2016. ''India and China''. New Delhi : International Academy of Indian Culture and Aditya Prakashan, 2016.\n*Chaudhuri, S. K. (2011). ''Sanskrit in China and Japan''. New Delhi: International Academy of Indian Culture and Aditya Prakashan. \n*Chellaney, Brahma, \"Rising Powers, Rising Tensions: The Troubled China-India Relationship,\" ''SAIS Review'' (2012) 32#2 pp.&nbsp;99\u2013108 [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/sais_review/v032/32.