{"title_page": "Sabine Brehm", "text_new": "{{short description|East German speed skater}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Sabine Brehm\n| image          = Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1988-1126-017, Sabine Brehm.jpg\n| caption        = Brehm in 1988\n| headercolor    = #d7ecff\n| country        = Germany<br>East Germany (1949-1990)\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1963|5|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight \t = \n| turnedpro      = \n| retired        = 1987\n|medaltemplates=\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women|World Allround Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[1985 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women|1985 Sarajevo]]|allround}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[1986 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women|1986 Den Haag]]|allround}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[European Speed Skating Championships for Women|European Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[1985 European Speed Skating Championships for Women|1985 Groningen]]|allround}}\n}}\n\n'''Sabine Brehm''' (born 5 May 1963) is a female former East-German [[Long track speed skating|long track speed skater]].<ref>[https://www.eurosport.de/eisschnelllauf/mund-kritisiert-wo-ist-die-analyse-nach-sotschi-geblieben_sto4500039/story.shtml]</ref> She represented her country at international competitions; as a senior until 1987.<ref>[https://www.speedskatingnews.info/de/data/skater/sabine-brehm/]</ref><ref>[http://www.speedskatingbase.eu/?section=skaters&subsection=skater&skaterid=2986]</ref>\n\nShe won the bronze medal at the [[1985 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women]] in Sarajevo and [[1986 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women]] in Den Haag. She also won the bronze allround medal at the [[1985 European Speed Skating Championships for Women]] in Groningen.\n\nBrehm won at the 1984 national championships the 3000m.\n\nShe rode two national records in 1985 and during her career a total of 8 track records.<ref>[https://www.speedskatingnews.info/de/data/skater/sabine-brehm/]</ref>\n\n== Records ==\n=== Personal records ===\n{{PersonalRecordsTop}}\n{{PersonalRecordsSport|Women's [[speed skating]]}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|500 m|41,70|09.02.1992|Sarajevo|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1000 m|1:23.82|02.12.1993|Karl-Marx-Stadt|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1500 m|2:06.15|10.02.1992|Sarajevo|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|3000 m|4:24.8|23.03.1989|Karuizawa|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|5000 m|7:43.79|10.02.1992|Sarajevo|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsBottom}}\n<ref>[https://www.speedskatingnews.info/de/data/skater/sabine-brehm/]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brehm, Sabine}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:East German sportswomen]]\n[[Category:Female speed skaters]]\n\n{{speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|East German speed skater}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Sabine Brehm\n| image          = Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1988-1126-017, Sabine Brehm.jpg\n| caption        = Brehm in 1988\n| headercolor    = #d7ecff\n| country        = Germany<br>East Germany (1949-1990)\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1963|5|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight \t = \n| turnedpro      = \n| retired        = 1987\n|medaltemplates=\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women|World Allround Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[1985 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women|1985 Sarajevo,]]|allround}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[1986 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women|1986 Den Haag]]|allround}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[European Speed Skating Championships for Women|European Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[1985 European Speed Skating Championships for Women|1985 Groningen]]|allround}}\n}}\n\n'''Sabine Brehm''' (born 5 May 1963) is a female former East-German [[Long track speed skating|long track speed skater]].<ref>[https://www.eurosport.de/eisschnelllauf/mund-kritisiert-wo-ist-die-analyse-nach-sotschi-geblieben_sto4500039/story.shtml]</ref> She represented her country at international competitions; as a senior until 1987.<ref>[https://www.speedskatingnews.info/de/data/skater/sabine-brehm/]</ref><ref>[http://www.speedskatingbase.eu/?section=skaters&subsection=skater&skaterid=2986]</ref>\n\nShe won the bronze medal at the [[1985 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women]] in Sarajevo and [[1986 World Allround Speed Skating Championships for Women]] in Den Haag. She also won the bronze allround medal at the [[1985 European Speed Skating Championships for Women]] in Groningen.\n\nBrehm won at the 1984 national championships the 3000m.\n\nShe rode two national records in 1985 and during her career a total of 8 track records.<ref>[https://www.speedskatingnews.info/de/data/skater/sabine-brehm/]</ref>\n\n== Records ==\n=== Personal records ===\n{{PersonalRecordsTop}}\n{{PersonalRecordsSport|Women's [[speed skating]]}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|500 m|41,70|09.02.1992|Sarajevo|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1000 m|1:23.82|02.12.1993|Karl-Marx-Stadt|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1500 m|2:06.15|10.02.1992|Sarajevo|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|3000 m|4:24.8|23.03.1989|Karuizawa|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|5000 m|7:43.79|10.02.1992|Sarajevo|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsBottom}}\n<ref>[https://www.speedskatingnews.info/de/data/skater/sabine-brehm/]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brehm, Sabine}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:East German sportswomen]]\n[[Category:Female speed skaters]]\n\n{{speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SportsOlympic", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabine_Brehm"}
