w.kentucky.com/news/health-and-medicine/article241173516.html |title=First Kentucky coronavirus patient is 'fully recovered,' discharged from UK hospital |website=kentucky.com |publisher=Lexington Herald-Leader |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316115904/https://www.kentucky.com/news/health-and-medicine/article241173516.html |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Minnesota: Governor Tim Walz declared a state of emergency and asked the state legislature to pass several emergency bills, including a bill to help speed up testing for the virus. He also urged that all events with 250 or more attendees be cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.minnpost.com/state-government/2020/03/walz-declares-state-of-emergency-for-minnesota-urges-canceling-or-postponing-all-large-events/ |title=Walz declares state of emergency for Minnesota, urges canceling or postponing all large events |date=2020-03-13 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150905/https://www.minnpost.com/state-government/2020/03/walz-declares-state-of-emergency-for-minnesota-urges-canceling-or-postponing-all-large-events/ |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Missouri: 2 more presumptive positive cases were reported, bring the total number of cases up to 4. [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]] declares a state of emergency and bans gatherings of over 250 people.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2020/03/13/st-louis-county-bans-events-of-more-than-250-people |title=St. Louis County Bans Events of More Than 250 People |last=Murphy |first=Doyle |website=Riverfront Times |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313201005/https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2020/03/13/st-louis-county-bans-events-of-more-than-250-people |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* New Hampshire: Governor Christopher Sununu declares state of emergency in New Hampshire due to Covid-19. Six cases are confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.nh.gov/news-media/orders-2020/documents/2020-04.pdf|title=Executive Order 2020-04 - An order declaring a state of emergency due to Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|last=Sununu|first=Christopher|date=March 13, 2020|website=State of New Hampshire Office of the Governor|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Oregon: governor announces a statewide K-12 school closure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ktvz.com/news/coronavirus/2020/03/12/gov-brown-announces-march-16-31-statewide-k-12-school-closure/|title=Gov. Brown announces March 16\u201331 statewide K-12 school closure|website=kztv.com|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320211349/https://ktvz.com/news/coronavirus/2020/03/12/gov-brown-announces-march-16-31-statewide-k-12-school-closure/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Pennsylvania: Governor [[Tom Wolf]] announced that all Pennsylvania schools will close for ten days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/pennsylvania-schools-closed-coronavirus/2325564/|title=Pennsylvania, Delaware Close All Schools Due to Outbreak|website=NBC10 Philadelphia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320202623/https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/pennsylvania-schools-closed-coronavirus/2325564/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rhode Island: 20 cases are confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/rhode-island/articles/2020-03-14/rhode-island-has-20-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-up-from-14?context=amp|title=Rhode Island Has 20 Confirmed Coronavirus Cases, up From 14|first=David|last=Klepper|date=March 14, 2020|website=usnews.com}}</ref>\n* South Carolina: Governor [[Henry McMaster]] declared a state of emergency and closed schools in [[Kershaw County, South Carolina|Kershaw]] and [[Lancaster County, South Carolina|Lancaster]] counties for 14 days due to there being evidence of the virus spreading in these counties.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web |url=https://wpde.com/news/local/sc-state-of-emergency-to-be-declared-to-enhance-response-to-coronavirus |title=State of emergency declared in SC to enhance response to coronavirus |last=Gale |first=Heather |date=2020-03-13 |publisher=WPDE-TV |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320202624/https://wpde.com/news/local/sc-state-of-emergency-to-be-declared-to-enhance-response-to-coronavirus |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* South Dakota: One new case in McCook County. Governor [[Kristi Noem]] declared a state of emergency across the state. All schools to close between March 16\u201320.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/friday-covid-19-south-dakota-update-1-more-positive-case/|title=Noem signs State of Emergency order; Requests schools to close throughout South Dakota next week |date=March 13, 2020|website=keloland.com}}</ref>\n* West Virginia: While the state still had no confirmed cases of COVID-19, Governor [[Jim Justice]] announced all schools across the state would close beginning on March 16, 2020 for an indefinite period of time as a proactive measure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |title=W.Va. Gov. Justice closing state schools indefinitely |last=Tierney |first=Brendan |date=March 13, 2020 |website=[[WSAZ-TV]] |language=english |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314093424/https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 14====\nThe total US cases passed 2,700. Five additional deaths were reported by state health departments: three in Washington, one in Florida, and one in Louisiana. In addition, New York's first death was reported in the news media and the governor of New Jersey announced the state's second death on Twitter. This brought reported deaths to 7 for the day.\n* North Carolina: All schools ordered to close for 2 weeks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/14/gov-roy-cooper-orders-nc-schools-close-least-weeks/ |title=Gov. Roy Cooper orders NC schools to close for at least 2 weeks |last=Lawson |first=Adam |date=March 14, 2020 |website=[[WBTV]] |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315050920/https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/14/gov-roy-cooper-orders-nc-schools-close-least-weeks/ |archive-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Governor Roy Cooper also issued an executive order to prevent mass gathering.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/14/gov-cooper-issues-executive-order-stop-mass-gatherings-nc/ |title=Gov. Cooper issues executive order to stop mass gatherings in NC |website=wbtv.com |publisher=WBTV Web |language=en-US |access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n* Ohio: Governor Mike DeWine and Department of Health Director [[Amy Acton]] on March 14 recommended Ohioans postpone elective surgeries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cleveland.com/open/2020/03/ohioans-should-postpone-many-elective-surgeries-because-of-coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-recommends.html |title=Ohioans should postpone many elective surgeries because of the coronavirus, Gov. Mike DeWine recommends |last=Pelzer |first=Jeremy |last2=clevel |date=2020-03-14 |website=cleveland |language=en |access-date=2020-03-16 |last3=.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316155149/https://www.cleveland.com/open/2020/03/ohioans-should-postpone-many-elective-surgeries-because-of-coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-recommends.html |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Oklahoma: Governor [[Kevin Stitt]] took a selfie with his family in a crowded restaurant. Stitt tweeted, \"It's packed tonight!\" and was criticized on social media for ignoring social distancing. Stitt deleted the tweet in response to the backlash.<ref>[https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/487811-states-lead-unevenly-on-coronavirus-response States lead, unevenly, on coronavirus response] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317165312/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/487811-states-lead-unevenly-on-coronavirus-response |date=March 17, 2020 }} The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n* Virginia: Governor [[Ralph Northam]] announced Virginia's first death from the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/14/virginia-first-coronavirus-death-129597 |title=Virginia governor announces state's first death from coronavirus |last=Semones |first=Evan |website=POLITICO |language=en |access-date=2020-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060801/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/14/virginia-first-coronavirus-death-129597 |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 15====\nOn March 15, the CDC issued guidance recommending against any gathering of 50 or more people for an eight-week period.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/cdc-recommends-the-cancellation-of-events-with-50-or-more-people-for-the-next-eight-weeks-throughout-us.html |title=CDC recommends canceling events with 50 or more people for the next eight weeks throughout US |last=Kopecki |first=Dawn |date=2020-03-15 |website=CNBC |language=en |access-date=2020-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318180317/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/cdc-recommends-the-cancellation-of-events-with-50-or-more-people-for-the-next-eight-weeks-throughout-us.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Alabama: The Alabama Department of Public Health counted 22 cases of coronavirus: Jefferson County, 12 cases; Tuscaloosa County, 3 cases; Shelby County, 2 cases; Baldwin County, Elmore, County, 