alth.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bringmethenews.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-news/minnesotas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-54 |title=Minnesota's confirmed coronavirus cases rise to 54 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317145512/https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-news/minnesotas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-54 |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Affected counties now include Anoka, [[Benton County, MN|Benton]], [[Blue Earth County, MN|Blue Earth]], Carver, Dakota, Hennepin, [[Olmsted County, MN|Olmsted]], [[Ramsey County, MN|Ramsey]], [[Renville County, MN|Renville]], Stearns, [[Sherburne County, MN|Sherburne]], [[Waseca County, MN|Waseca]], [[Washington County, MN|Washington]], and [[Wright County, MN|Wright]].<ref name=\"bringmethenews.com\" /> Governor Tim Walz has ordered the closure of public places, including all: restaurants, bars, coffee shops, gyms, theaters, breweries, ski resorts, and other public places until at least March 27. Bars and restaurants in the state were closed only to dine in customers; the businesses were allowed to continue to serve customers by take out or delivery orders. He said this order may be extended.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |title=Walz temporarily closes bars, restaurants and gyms to curb COVID-19 spread |last=MPR Staff |website=Minnesota Public Radio |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317231710/https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Ohio: The state has 50 confirmed cases of COVID-19. Bowling alleys, fitness centers, gyms, movie theaters, public recreation centers, trampoline parks, and water parks are ordered to be shut<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200316/coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-closes-gyms-recreation-centers |title=Coronavirus: Gov. Mike DeWine closes gyms, recreation centers |last=Wagner |first=Mike |date=March 16, 2020 |website=dispatch.com |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318061227/https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200316/coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-closes-gyms-recreation-centers |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and gatherings of more than 50 people are banned.<ref name= \"CBS10 TIMELINE\"/> DeWine announces the [[United States presidential primary|presidential primary elections]], scheduled for the next day, will be cancelled on orders of Department of Health director Amy Acton.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/politics/primary-elections-coronavirus/index.html |title=States move forward with Tuesday elections as coronavirus pandemic alters American life |last=Gallagher |first=Dianne |last2=Kirkland |first2=Pamela |website=CNN |access-date=17 March 2020 |last3=Sullivan |first3=Kate |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317193715/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/politics/primary-elections-coronavirus/index.html |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Oklahoma: Governor Stitt declares a state of emergency after being criticized for ignoring social distancing. Ten cases of coronavirus are confirmed in the state.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/15/politics/oklahoma-governor-deleted-tweet-coronavirus/index.html Oklahoma governor who faced backlash over 'packed' restaurant tweet now declares state of emergency] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318053644/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/15/politics/oklahoma-governor-deleted-tweet-coronavirus/index.html |date=March 18, 2020 }} CNN, 16 Mar 2020</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kfor.com/health/coronavirus/oklahoma-coronavirus-cases-jump-to-10-dozens-of-tests-pending/